var tafsirData_5 = {
  1: {
    "O believers!": "This is a direct address from Allah to those who have faith. Whenever Allah begins with this phrase, it signals that something important is about to be commanded or prohibited. It is a call to pay attention because what follows is crucial for your faith and daily life.",
    "Honour your obligations.": "This is a comprehensive command to fulfill all contracts, promises, and agreements you make. This includes agreements between you and Allah (like following His commands), agreements between you and other people (like business deals, marriage contracts, and promises), and even agreements with yourself. The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) said that the signs of a hypocrite include breaking promises and betraying trusts. So honoring your word is a fundamental characteristic of a true believer. For example, if you agree to sell something at a certain price, you must stick to that agreement. If you promise to help someone, you should follow through.",
    "All grazing livestock has been made lawful to you": "Allah is informing believers that animals like cattle, sheep, goats, and camels are permissible for you to eat. These animals graze on grass and plants, and Allah has made them a blessing and provision for humanity. This establishes the general rule that these animals are halal (lawful) for consumption.",
    "—except what is hereby announced to you": "However, there are specific exceptions that will be detailed shortly (in the coming verses). Not everything is automatically permissible; certain conditions and restrictions apply. This teaches us that even in matters of what we eat, we must follow Allah's guidelines.",
    "and hunting while on pilgrimage.": "When you are in the state of ihram (the sacred state during Hajj or Umrah pilgrimage), hunting land animals becomes forbidden. This is a test of self-control and respect for the sacred journey. Even though hunting might normally be allowed, during this special spiritual time, you must refrain from it.",
    "Indeed, Allah commands what He wills.": "Allah has the absolute right to make any ruling He wishes. He is the Creator and Lawgiver, and His wisdom is perfect even if we don't fully understand it. This reminds us to submit to His commands with trust and acceptance."
  },
  2: {
    "O believers! Do not violate Allah's rituals ˹of pilgrimage˺,": "Allah commands believers not to disrespect or treat lightly the sacred rites and symbols associated with worship, especially those related to Hajj. These rituals were established by Allah and must be honored. This includes all the acts of pilgrimage like circling the Kaaba, standing at Arafat, and other prescribed acts.",
    "the sacred months,": "There are four sacred months in the Islamic calendar: Dhul-Qa'dah, Dhul-Hijjah, Muharram, and Rajab. During these months, fighting and warfare were traditionally forbidden even before Islam, and Islam confirmed their sanctity. Violating the peace of these months by initiating conflict is a serious sin.",
    "the sacrificial animals,": "Animals designated for sacrifice during Hajj or as an offering to Allah must be respected. They are set apart for a sacred purpose and should not be harmed, stolen, or used for any other purpose before they reach their destination.",
    "the ˹offerings decorated with˺ garlands,": "In those times, animals intended for sacrifice were marked with garlands around their necks to indicate they were sacred offerings. This marking meant they should be left alone and allowed to reach the Kaaba safely. No one should harm or obstruct these animals.",
    "nor those ˹pilgrims˺ on their way to the Sacred House seeking their Lord's bounty and pleasure.": "Pilgrims traveling to Makkah for Hajj or Umrah must be protected and not harassed, regardless of who they are or where they come from. They are on a spiritual journey seeking Allah's blessings and rewards, and obstructing them is forbidden. This was especially significant because before Islam, tribes would sometimes attack travelers even during pilgrimage seasons.",
    "When pilgrimage has ended, you are allowed to hunt.": "Once you have completed your Hajj or Umrah and exited the state of ihram, the restriction on hunting is lifted. You may resume hunting for food. This shows that the prohibition was temporary and specific to the sacred state of pilgrimage.",
    "Do not let the hatred of a people who once barred you from the Sacred Mosque provoke you to transgress.": "This is a profound principle of justice. The Quraysh of Makkah had previously prevented the Muslims from performing Umrah at Hudaybiyyah. Despite this injustice, Allah tells the believers not to let their anger lead them to retaliate unjustly. Your emotions should not control your actions. Even if someone wrongs you, you must still act with justice and not exceed the limits set by Allah. This is a high standard of moral conduct that Islam demands.",
    "Cooperate with one another in goodness and righteousness,": "Believers should help each other in doing good deeds, acts of worship, charity, and anything that pleases Allah. When you see someone trying to do something good, support them. Build a community based on mutual assistance in what is right.",
    "and do not cooperate in sin and transgression.": "Just as you should help in good, you must refuse to assist in anything sinful or harmful. If someone asks you to help them cheat, lie, harm someone, or do anything forbidden, you must decline. Being part of wrongdoing—even as a helper—makes you share in the sin.",
    "And be mindful of Allah.": "Have taqwa—be conscious that Allah is watching everything you do. This awareness should guide all your decisions and prevent you from wrongdoing.",
    "Surely Allah is severe in punishment.": "While Allah is Most Merciful, He is also severe in punishing those who persist in disobedience and transgression. This balance of hope and fear keeps believers on the straight path."
  },
  3: {
    "Forbidden to you are carrion,": "Any animal that dies on its own without proper slaughter is not permissible to eat. This includes animals that die from disease, old age, or any natural cause. The wisdom behind this includes health reasons—such meat may carry diseases—and spiritual reasons—it was not slaughtered with Allah's name.",
    "blood,": "Flowing blood that comes out during slaughter is forbidden to consume. This is different from the small amount of blood that remains in meat after proper slaughter, which is unavoidable and permissible. Drinking or consuming blood was a practice among some pre-Islamic Arabs and is prohibited in Islam.",
    "and swine;": "Pork and all products from pigs are completely forbidden. This is a clear prohibition that has no exceptions (except in cases of absolute necessity to survive). Modern science has shown various health concerns with pork, but ultimately, we obey because Allah commanded it.",
    "what is slaughtered in the name of any other than Allah;": "Any animal over which a name other than Allah's was invoked at slaughter—such as idols, saints, or other deities—is forbidden. This protects the purity of our worship and ensures we do not participate in or support polytheistic practices.",
    "what is killed by strangling,": "An animal that dies from being choked or strangled is not permissible. Proper Islamic slaughter requires cutting the throat to allow blood to drain, which is more humane and healthier.",
    "beating,": "An animal beaten to death is forbidden. This was a cruel practice where animals were clubbed until they died, which is both inhumane and does not allow proper blood drainage.",
    "a fall,": "If an animal falls from a height and dies from the impact, it is not permissible to eat unless you reach it while it's still alive and slaughter it properly.",
    "or by being gored to death;": "An animal killed by the horns of another animal is forbidden. Again, unless you find it still alive and slaughter it properly, it cannot be eaten.",
    "what is partly eaten by a predator unless you slaughter it;": "If a wild animal like a wolf or lion attacks an animal and partially eats it, the remains are forbidden—unless you reach the animal while it's still showing signs of life and you slaughter it properly with Allah's name.",
    "and what is sacrificed on altars.": "Animals slaughtered on stone altars dedicated to idols, as was common in pre-Islamic Arabia, are forbidden. This practice was associated with idol worship, and consuming such meat would mean participating in that false worship.",
    "You are also forbidden to draw lots for decisions.": "Using arrows or any form of lottery to make decisions about what is lawful or unlawful, or to divine the future, is prohibited. This was a superstitious practice where people would seek guidance from chance rather than from Allah. Muslims should make decisions through prayer (istikhara), consultation, and rational thinking—not superstition.",
    "This is all evil.": "All these prohibited things are described as fisq—wickedness and deviation from the right path. Engaging in any of these takes a person away from righteousness.",
    "Today the disbelievers have given up all hope of ˹undermining˺ your faith.": "This verse was revealed during the Farewell Pilgrimage, near the end of the Prophet's life. By this time, Islam had become strong and established. The enemies of Islam realized they could no longer destroy or corrupt the religion. This was a moment of victory and reassurance for the believers.",
    "So do not fear them; fear Me!": "Since the disbelievers can no longer harm your religion, there is no reason to fear them. Instead, focus your fear and reverence on Allah alone. He is the only one whose displeasure you should truly worry about.",
    "Today I have perfected your faith for you,": "This momentous declaration came during the Prophet's final Hajj. It means that all the laws, guidance, and teachings of Islam have been completed. Nothing essential is missing. When Umar ibn al-Khattab heard this verse, he wept because he understood it signaled the approaching end of the Prophet's mission and life.",
    "completed My favour upon you,": "Allah's favor of guidance, legislation, protection, and victory has been fully granted to the Muslim community. The greatest favor is the guidance of Islam itself.",
    "and chosen Islam as your way.": "Allah has selected Islam—meaning complete submission to Him—as the religion He approves for humanity. No other way of life is acceptable to Him after this completion. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said that Allah will not accept any religion other than Islam from anyone.",
    "But whoever is compelled by extreme hunger—": "In cases of dire necessity, where a person is starving and faces death, the prohibitions are relaxed. If you are in a situation where you will die without eating, and the only available food is something forbidden, you are allowed to eat just enough to survive.",
    "not intending to sin—": "This permission is only for genuine emergencies, not for someone looking for an excuse to eat forbidden things. Your intention must be purely survival, not enjoyment of the forbidden or deliberate disobedience.",
    "then surely Allah is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful.": "Allah understands human weakness and difficult circumstances. He will not punish someone who was forced by necessity to do what is normally forbidden, as long as they had the right intention and did not exceed what was necessary."
  },
  4: {
    "They ask you, ˹O Prophet,˺ what is permissible for them ˹to eat˺.": "The companions of the Prophet (peace be upon him) would frequently ask him questions about what was allowed and what was forbidden. This shows their eagerness to follow Allah's commands correctly. This particular question was about what foods they could eat.",
    "Say, \"What is good and lawful.": "The Prophet is instructed to tell them that all good, pure, and wholesome things are permissible. Islam does not make life difficult; rather, it allows everything that is beneficial and pure while only prohibiting what is harmful or impure.",
    "Also what is caught by your hunting animals and birds of prey which you have trained as instructed by Allah.": "Trained hunting animals like dogs, falcons, and hawks can catch game for you. The key conditions are: the animal must be properly trained (meaning it catches for you and returns, not eating the prey itself), and the training should be done according to proper methods. Dogs that are trained for hunting are an exception to the general ruling about dogs, showing Islam's practical approach.",
    "So eat what they catch for you,": "If your trained hunting animal catches prey and holds it for you without eating it, that prey is lawful even if it dies before you can slaughter it. This is a special permission because proper slaughter may not always be possible when hunting.",
    "but mention the Name of Allah over it ˹first˺.\"": "When you send your hunting animal, you must say \"Bismillah\" (In the name of Allah). This makes the catch permissible. The Prophet (peace be upon him) taught that if you forget to say Allah's name when sending the animal, you should not eat what it catches.",
    "And be mindful of Allah.": "In all matters of eating and hunting, maintain consciousness of Allah. Don't be excessive, don't be cruel to animals, and always remember that these permissions come with responsibilities.",
    "Surely Allah is swift in reckoning.": "Allah's accounting is comprehensive and quick. Every action, including how you obtain and consume your food, will be accounted for. This encourages believers to be careful and follow the rules sincerely."
  },
  5: {
    "Today all good, pure foods have been made lawful for you.": "Allah reiterates that wholesome, pure foods are permissible for Muslims. Islam is not about deprivation; it is about enjoying Allah's blessings within proper boundaries.",
    "Similarly, the food of the People of the Book is permissible for you": "Jews and Christians (People of the Book) who slaughter animals according to their religious traditions—their meat is permissible for Muslims to eat. This shows Islam's recognition of the shared Abrahamic heritage and facilitates social interaction between these communities. However, the food must still meet basic requirements (not pork, for example).",
    "and yours is permissible for them.": "Muslim food is also permissible for Jews and Christians to eat. This mutual permission creates a basis for hospitality and sharing between communities.",
    "And ˹permissible for you in marriage˺ are chaste believing women": "Muslim men may marry chaste Muslim women. Chastity here refers to women who guard their honor and are not involved in illicit relationships.",
    "as well as chaste women of those given the Scripture before you": "Muslim men are also permitted to marry chaste Jewish or Christian women. This permission has conditions: the women must be practicing their faith and be chaste. This allowance has existed throughout Islamic history and shows Islam's approach to coexistence. However, many scholars advise caution because of the challenges in raising children with a shared Islamic identity.",
    "—as long as you pay them their dowries in wedlock,": "Marriage must be conducted properly with a mahr (dowry) given to the bride. This is her right and a symbol of the husband's commitment and responsibility.",
    "neither fornicating nor taking them as mistresses.": "The relationship must be a proper marriage, not fornication (casual relations) or taking mistresses (secret girlfriends). Islam only recognizes the honorable bond of marriage for intimate relationships. Any relationship outside of marriage is sinful, regardless of how society might normalize it.",
    "And whoever rejects the faith,": "This is a serious warning. If someone abandons their faith or denies the fundamental beliefs of Islam—",
    "all their good deeds will be void ˹in this life˺": "All their previous good works become worthless. Just as a computer file gets corrupted and becomes useless, so do deeds when faith is rejected. Good deeds only count when accompanied by true faith.",
    "and in the Hereafter they will be among the losers.": "On the Day of Judgment, they will have nothing to show for their life and will face eternal loss. This emphasizes that faith is the foundation upon which all deeds are built."
  },
  6: {
    "O believers! When you rise up for prayer,": "When you intend to perform prayer, there are steps of purification you must complete first. Prayer is a meeting with Allah, and just as you would prepare to meet someone important, you must prepare to stand before your Lord.",
    "wash your faces": "The face must be washed completely, from the hairline to the chin and from ear to ear. This is the first step of wudu (ablution). Water should reach all parts of the face, including the beard for men.",
    "and your hands up to the elbows,": "Both arms must be washed from the fingertips up to and including the elbows. This ensures the limbs you use most in daily activities are cleansed before prayer.",
    "wipe your heads,": "Pass wet hands over the head. The minimum is wiping part of the head, though wiping the entire head is the sunnah of the Prophet (peace be upon him).",
    "and wash your feet to the ankles.": "Both feet must be washed up to and including the ankles. The Prophet emphasized washing between the toes and ensuring water reaches all parts of the feet. He warned that heels not properly washed would face the Fire.",
    "And if you are in a state of ˹full˺ impurity,": "Full impurity (janabah) occurs after sexual intercourse or ejaculation. In this state, wudu alone is not sufficient.",
    "then take a full bath.": "A complete bath (ghusl) is required, washing the entire body and ensuring water reaches every part, including rinsing the mouth and nose.",
    "But if you are ill,": "If using water would harm you due to illness—such as causing pain or delaying recovery—an alternative is provided.",
    "on a journey,": "Travelers sometimes have difficulty finding or accessing water, so Allah provides flexibility.",
    "or have relieved yourselves,": "After using the bathroom, wudu is broken and must be renewed.",
    "or have been intimate with your wives": "After sexual relations, purification through ghusl is required.",
    "and cannot find water,": "When water is genuinely unavailable after searching, or using it would cause harm—",
    "then purify yourselves with clean earth by wiping your faces and hands.": "This is tayammum—the dry purification. You strike clean earth (soil, sand, or dust) with your hands and wipe your face and hands. This remarkable concession shows Allah's mercy and the practicality of Islamic law.",
    "It is not Allah's Will to burden you,": "Allah does not want to make religion difficult. The purpose is not to create hardship but to maintain worship even in challenging circumstances.",
    "but to purify you": "The goal of wudu, ghusl, and tayammum is purification—both physical and spiritual. These acts prepare the heart and body for standing before Allah.",
    "and complete His favour upon you,": "Every command from Allah is actually a favor. By teaching us how to purify ourselves, Allah is completing His blessing upon us.",
    "so perhaps you will be grateful.": "When we recognize that even these rituals are blessings designed for our benefit, we should respond with gratitude and willingly perform them."
  },
  7: {
    "Remember Allah's favour upon you": "Never forget the countless blessings Allah has given you—the blessing of Islam, guidance, provision, health, and everything else. Gratitude keeps the heart attached to Allah and prevents arrogance.",
    "and the covenant He made with you": "When you became Muslim, you made a covenant with Allah. This covenant includes believing in Him, following His Messenger, and obeying His commands. Every believer enters into this agreement.",
    "when you said, \"We hear and obey.\"": "This was the response of the believers when they accepted Islam—full submission without conditions. Unlike those who said \"we hear and disobey,\" true believers accept Allah's commands wholeheartedly, even when they don't fully understand the wisdom behind them.",
    "And be mindful of Allah.": "Maintain awareness of Allah in all your affairs. Your covenant is not just words; it requires continuous consciousness and action.",
    "Surely Allah knows best what is ˹hidden˺ in the heart.": "You cannot deceive Allah. He knows your true intentions, secret thoughts, and hidden feelings. Even if you appear religious outwardly, Allah knows the reality of your inner state. This should motivate sincerity in all our worship and dealings."
  },
  8: {
    "O believers! Stand firm for Allah": "Be consistent and unwavering in your commitment to Allah. This means standing up for truth, justice, and His commands even when it's difficult or unpopular.",
    "and bear true testimony.": "When you are called to testify, speak the truth even if it goes against your own interests or the interests of people you love. False testimony is a major sin that corrupts society and denies people their rights.",
    "Do not let the hatred of a people lead you to injustice.": "Even if you have legitimate grievances against a group—even if they have wronged you—you must still treat them justly. Your anger or hatred cannot be an excuse for unfair treatment. This is one of the highest ethical standards Islam demands.",
    "Be just!": "A direct, emphatic command. Justice must be maintained regardless of circumstances, personal feelings, or who is involved. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said that the just will be on pulpits of light on the Day of Judgment.",
    "That is closer to righteousness.": "Acting justly, especially when it's hard, brings you closer to taqwa (consciousness of Allah). It purifies your heart and elevates your character.",
    "And be mindful of Allah.": "Remember that Allah is watching how you treat others, especially those you dislike. Your taqwa is tested most when dealing with those you have reason to resent.",
    "Surely Allah is All-Aware of what you do.": "Nothing escapes Allah's knowledge. Every just or unjust act is recorded, and you will be held accountable for how you treated people."
  },
  9: {
    "Allah has promised those who believe and do good": "This promise comes from Allah Himself, and He never breaks His promises. Note that belief alone is mentioned alongside good deeds—true faith must be accompanied by righteous action.",
    "˹His˺ forgiveness": "Allah will forgive their sins, overlook their shortcomings, and not hold them accountable for their mistakes if they sincerely repent and strive to do good. This forgiveness erases sins from the record.",
    "and a great reward.": "Beyond forgiveness, there is Paradise with its unimaginable delights—rewards that no eye has seen, no ear has heard, and no heart has imagined. This motivates believers to persevere through difficulties knowing that an immense reward awaits."
  },
  10: {
    "As for those who disbelieve and deny Our signs,": "Those who reject faith and refuse to accept Allah's revelations, guidance, and proof—",
    "they are the residents of the Hellfire.": "Their permanent abode will be Hell. This is stated matter-of-factly to emphasize the seriousness of disbelief. The contrast with the previous verse is stark: believers get Paradise, disbelievers get Hell. This should motivate everyone to seek the truth sincerely."
  },
  11: {
    "O believers! Remember Allah's favour upon you:": "Recall and reflect upon the times when Allah protected you from harm. This remembrance increases gratitude and trust in Allah.",
    "when a people sought to harm you,": "There were occasions when enemies planned to attack or harm the Muslim community. Some scholars mention a specific incident where a group planned to assassinate the Prophet (peace be upon him).",
    "but He held their hands back from you.": "Allah intervened and prevented them from carrying out their evil plans. Whether through sending down fear into their hearts, creating obstacles, or other means—Allah protected the believers. This happened numerous times in Islamic history.",
    "Be mindful of Allah.": "Recognizing Allah's protection should increase your taqwa. When you see how He saved you before, you should trust Him more and obey Him better.",
    "And in Allah let the believers put their trust.": "Tawakkul (reliance on Allah) is a fundamental quality of believers. This doesn't mean being passive—you take necessary precautions—but your heart relies completely on Allah for the outcome. When you've done your part, trust that Allah will handle what you cannot control."
  },
  12: {
    "Allah made a covenant with the Children of Israel": "Allah entered into a solemn agreement with the descendants of Prophet Ya'qub (Jacob), peace be upon him. This covenant established their responsibilities and the blessings they would receive in return for obedience.",
    "and appointed twelve leaders from among them": "For each of the twelve tribes of Israel, Allah designated a leader (naqib) to represent and guide their tribe. These leaders were responsible for ensuring their people upheld the covenant.",
    "and ˹then˺ said, \"I am truly with you.": "Allah promised His divine support, help, and presence with them. Being \"with\" them means His protection, guidance, and aid—not physical presence, as Allah is above His creation.",
    "If you establish prayer,": "The first condition: maintaining regular prayer with all its requirements, performed properly and on time. Prayer is the foundation of the relationship with Allah.",
    "pay alms-tax,": "The second condition: giving zakah (obligatory charity) to purify wealth and help those in need. This was required in their law as it is in ours.",
    "believe in My messengers,": "The third condition: accepting and following all the prophets Allah sends, not just some of them. This would later include believing in Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him).",
    "support them,": "The fourth condition: actively helping and assisting the messengers in their mission, defending them and their message.",
    "and lend to Allah a good loan,": "The fifth condition: spending in Allah's cause generously and sincerely. When you give charity for Allah's sake, it's described as a \"loan\" to Allah—but Allah returns it multiplied many times over.",
    "I will certainly forgive your sins": "If they fulfilled these conditions, Allah promised to erase their sins and wrongdoings.",
    "and admit you into Gardens under which rivers flow.": "They would be granted Paradise, with its beautiful gardens and flowing rivers—eternal bliss as a reward for their faithfulness.",
    "And whoever among you disbelieves afterwards has truly strayed from the Right Way.\"": "Despite all these favors and clear conditions, whoever chose to disbelieve after knowing the truth had abandoned the straight path. They had no excuse for their misguidance."
  },
  13: {
    "But for breaking their covenant,": "Despite the clear terms and generous rewards, the Children of Israel violated their agreement with Allah. They did not fulfill the conditions they had agreed to.",
    "We condemned them": "Allah's curse (la'nah) fell upon them—they were distanced from His mercy. This is a severe consequence of breaking covenants with Allah.",
    "and hardened their hearts.": "As a result of their continuous disobedience, their hearts became hard and unreceptive to guidance. When a person repeatedly ignores truth, their heart eventually loses sensitivity. This is a warning to all of us: don't let sin harden your heart.",
    "They distorted the words of the Scripture": "They changed the meanings of their holy texts, either by altering the actual words or by misinterpreting them deliberately. This is called tahrif—distortion. They made permissible what was forbidden and vice versa to suit their desires.",
    "and neglected a portion of what they had been commanded to uphold.": "They abandoned parts of their Scripture that they found inconvenient. They practiced selective religion, following what suited them and ignoring what didn't. This is a warning against cherry-picking in religion.",
    "You ˹O Prophet˺ will always find deceit on their part, except for a few.": "The Prophet (peace be upon him) is informed that most of them will continue in their deceptive ways. Only a minority—sincere individuals like Abdullah ibn Salam, a Jewish scholar who embraced Islam—would be truthful.",
    "But pardon them and bear with them.": "Despite their behavior, the Prophet is commanded to show patience and forgiveness. This demonstrates the beautiful character Islam demands from believers, especially leaders.",
    "Indeed, Allah loves the good-doers.": "Those who respond to evil with good, who pardon when they could punish, are beloved to Allah. This motivates believers to maintain excellence in character even when wronged."
  },
  14: {
    "And from those who say, \"We are Christians,\"": "Allah now addresses those who claim to be followers of Christ (peace be upon him). They too were given a covenant.",
    "We took their covenant,": "Christians also entered into an agreement with Allah through Prophet Isa (Jesus), peace be upon him, to follow his true teachings and await the final Prophet.",
    "but they neglected a portion of what they had been commanded to uphold.": "Like the Jews before them, Christians also abandoned parts of their Scripture. They invented new doctrines not taught by Jesus (peace be upon him), such as the Trinity, and left behind pure monotheism.",
    "So We let hostility and enmity arise between them until the Day of Judgment,": "As a consequence of abandoning their covenant, Allah caused them to divide into opposing sects that have fought each other throughout history. Catholics, Orthodox, Protestants, and countless other denominations have been in conflict for centuries. This disunity is a result of straying from the original message.",
    "and soon Allah will inform them of all they have done.": "On the Day of Judgment, Allah will show them exactly how they deviated from the truth. Every innovation, every distortion, and every act of disobedience will be made clear to them."
  },
  15: {
    "O People of the Book!": "Allah addresses the Jews and Christians directly, calling them by a respected title that acknowledges their previous scriptures.",
    "Now Our Messenger has come to you,": "Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) has arrived as the final messenger. His coming was prophesied in their own scriptures, though they tried to hide those prophecies.",
    "revealing much of what you have hidden of the Scriptures": "The Prophet exposes many things they deliberately concealed—descriptions of the final Prophet, laws they changed for convenience, and truths they buried. For example, they had hidden verses about stoning for adultery, and prophecies about Ahmad (another name for Muhammad).",
    "and disregarding much.": "At the same time, he doesn't expose everything they hid—only what is necessary. This shows mercy and wisdom; there's no need to embarrass them about every single thing.",
    "There certainly has come to you from Allah a light": "This light refers to Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) himself, who illuminates the path of guidance and dispels the darkness of ignorance and misguidance.",
    "and a clear Book": "The Quran has been revealed—a book that is clear in its guidance, unambiguous in its core message, and preserved from corruption. Unlike previous scriptures that were altered, the Quran remains exactly as it was revealed."
  },
  16: {
    "through which Allah guides those who seek His pleasure": "This Book (the Quran) guides those who sincerely want to please Allah. Guidance is given to those who seek it earnestly, not to those who arrogantly reject it.",
    "to the ways of peace,": "Islam guides to paths of peace—peace with Allah through worship, peace with oneself through inner tranquility, and peace with others through justice and mercy. Salaam (peace) is connected to the word Islam itself.",
    "brings them out of darkness and into light by His Will,": "Those who follow the Quran are rescued from the multiple darknesses of ignorance, disbelief, sin, and confusion, and brought into the single light of truth and guidance. This happens only by Allah's permission and grace.",
    "and guides them to the Straight Path.": "The ultimate goal is the straight path leading to Paradise—the path of the prophets and righteous people throughout history. This is the same path believers ask for in every prayer: \"Guide us to the straight path.\""
  },
  17: {
    "Indeed, those who say, \"Allah is the Messiah, son of Mary,\" have fallen into disbelief.": "This directly addresses the Christian belief that Jesus is God. The Quran categorically states that this belief is disbelief (kufr). Jesus (peace be upon him) was a noble prophet and messenger, but he was not divine. He himself worshipped Allah and never claimed divinity.",
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Who has the power to prevent Allah if He chose to destroy the Messiah, son of Mary,": "Here is a logical argument: If Jesus were God, he would be all-powerful. But Allah could destroy Jesus if He willed, and no one could stop Him. This proves Jesus cannot be God, because God cannot be destroyed or overpowered.",
    "his mother,": "Similarly, Mary (peace be upon her), though greatly honored, was a human being completely dependent on Allah for her existence.",
    "and everyone in the world all together?\"": "Allah could destroy all of creation if He wished. No one has the power to prevent what Allah decrees. This demonstrates that all created beings—including Jesus and Mary—are subject to Allah's will and power.",
    "To Allah ˹alone˺ belongs the kingdom of the heavens and the earth and everything in between.": "Allah is the sole owner and master of everything that exists. The heavens, the earth, and all that lies between them belong to Him alone. No one shares in His dominion.",
    "He creates whatever He wills.": "Allah creates freely according to His wisdom. He created Jesus without a father, just as He created Adam without parents. Creating in an unusual way doesn't make the creation divine.",
    "And Allah is Most Capable of everything.": "There is nothing beyond Allah's power. This statement affirms His unlimited ability and reinforces that Jesus, being created, cannot share in this divine attribute of absolute power."
  },
  18: {
    "The Jews and the Christians each say, \"We are the children of Allah and His most beloved!\"": "Both groups claimed a special, exclusive relationship with Allah—that they were His chosen children whom He especially loved. This gave them a sense of superiority and made them believe they were guaranteed salvation regardless of their actions.",
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Why then does He punish you for your sins?": "This is a powerful rebuttal. If you were truly Allah's beloved children, why has He allowed you to suffer and be punished throughout history? A loving parent doesn't punish innocent children. Your punishment proves you are accountable just like everyone else.",
    "No! You are only humans like others of His Own making.": "This dismantles their claim to special status. You are human beings just like all other human beings. You have no inherent superiority based on your ethnic or religious identity. All humans were created by Allah and are equally subject to His judgment.",
    "He forgives whoever He wills and punishes whoever He wills.": "Forgiveness and punishment are based on Allah's wisdom and justice, not on belonging to a particular group. A Jew or Christian who obeys Allah will be treated according to their deeds, just like anyone else. There are no guarantees based on labels.",
    "To Allah ˹alone˺ belongs the kingdom of the heavens and the earth and everything in between.": "Repeated for emphasis: Allah is the sole sovereign. His decisions about who to forgive and punish are His alone to make.",
    "And to Him is the final return.": "Everyone will return to Allah for judgment. This is the great equalizer—no one escapes accountability, and everyone will be judged by the same just standard."
  },
  19: {
    "O People of the Book!": "Another direct address to Jews and Christians, emphasizing the importance of what follows.",
    "Our Messenger has indeed come to you,": "Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) has been sent to you. His mission is not just for the Arabs but for all humanity, including the People of the Book.",
    "making things clear to you": "He clarifies the truth, explains what was ambiguous, restores what was distorted, and provides complete guidance for life.",
    "after an interval between the messengers": "There was a gap of approximately 600 years between Jesus and Muhammad (peace be upon them both). During this period, no new messenger was sent, and the previous scriptures became corrupted.",
    "so you do not say, \"There has never come to us a deliverer of good news or a warner.\"": "Allah sent Muhammad so that on the Day of Judgment, no one can claim they didn't receive guidance. The excuse \"we didn't know\" or \"no one told us\" has been removed.",
    "Now there has come to you a deliverer of good news and a warner.": "Muhammad (peace be upon him) brings both good news (of Paradise for believers) and warnings (of Hell for disbelievers). He fulfills both roles, and his message is complete.",
    "And Allah is Most Capable of everything.": "Allah is capable of sending messengers, preserving His message, and bringing about the Day of Judgment when all excuses will be rendered useless."
  },
  20: {
    "And ˹remember˺ when Moses said to his people, \"O my people!": "Prophet Musa (Moses) addresses his people, the Children of Israel, with affection and care, calling them \"my people\" to emphasize their connection.",
    "Remember Allah's favours upon you": "He asks them to reflect on the many blessings Allah has given them. Gratitude is essential for maintaining blessings and earning more.",
    "when He raised prophets from among you,": "Allah blessed the Children of Israel with numerous prophets—more than any other nation. This was a tremendous honor and source of guidance.",
    "made you sovereign,": "After being slaves in Egypt, Allah liberated them and gave them independence and authority. Some scholars explain this as each household being free and self-governing, or that they were given kingdoms and power.",
    "and gave you what He had never given anyone in the world.\"": "They received unique blessings: the parting of the sea, manna and quails from heaven, water from rocks, shade from clouds in the desert, and direct revelation to their prophet. No nation before them had received such miraculous favors."
  },
  21: {
    "O my people! Enter the Holy Land": "Moses commands them to enter the blessed land of Palestine/Jerusalem, which Allah had promised to them.",
    "which Allah has destined for you ˹to enter˺.": "This was written for them by divine decree—it was their destiny and inheritance if they obeyed Allah. The land was promised to them as faithful servants of Allah.",
    "And do not turn back": "Don't retreat, don't flee, don't abandon this mission out of fear or weakness.",
    "or else you will become losers.\"": "Turning back from Allah's command always results in loss—loss of worldly blessings and, more importantly, loss in the Hereafter."
  },
  22: {
    "They replied, \"O Moses! There is an enormously powerful people there,": "Instead of trusting in Allah's promise, they focused on the strength of their enemies—the Canaanite giants who inhabited the land. Fear of the enemy overshadowed their faith in Allah.",
    "so we will never ˹be able to˺ enter it until they leave.": "They made a categorical refusal. They wouldn't even try. They expected the enemy to voluntarily abandon their homes—an unrealistic excuse to avoid effort and sacrifice.",
    "If they do, then we will enter!\"": "Their cowardly condition: they would only enter if there was no resistance. This shows complete lack of faith in Allah's power and promise. They wanted victory without any struggle."
  },
  23: {
    "Two God-fearing men—who had been blessed by Allah—said,": "Among them were two righteous men, Joshua (Yusha') and Caleb, who had true faith. They had scouted the land and seen the same giants but drew different conclusions because they trusted in Allah.",
    "\"Surprise them through the gate.": "They gave practical military advice: enter suddenly through the gate, catch them off guard. This shows that faith doesn't mean abandoning strategy—you plan and then rely on Allah.",
    "If you do, you will certainly prevail.": "With Allah's help and a surprise attack, victory was assured. The size of the enemy doesn't matter when Allah is on your side.",
    "Put your trust in Allah if you are ˹truly˺ believers.\"": "They reminded their people that trust in Allah is a requirement of faith. If you truly believe, you must trust that Allah will fulfill His promise. Fear of creation contradicts faith in the Creator."
  },
  24: {
    "˹Yet˺ they said, \"O Moses! ˹Still˺ we will never enter as long as they remain there.": "Despite the encouragement from their righteous brothers, the majority stubbornly refused. Their fear had overwhelmed their faith completely.",
    "So go—both you and your Lord—and fight;": "This shocking statement shows their complete abandonment of their duty. They actually told Moses that he and Allah (!) should go fight while they stayed behind. This is the height of disrespect and disobedience.",
    "we are staying right here!\"": "They chose cowardice and disobedience over trust and effort. This would have severe consequences. Their statement represents the worst kind of response to a divine command—outright refusal combined with mockery."
  },
  25: {
    "Moses pleaded, \"My Lord! I have no control over anyone except myself and my brother.": "Moses, frustrated and hurt by his people's refusal, turns to Allah. He distances himself from their rebellion, affirming that only he and his brother Harun (Aaron) are obedient. He acknowledges he cannot force anyone to have faith.",
    "So set us apart from the rebellious people.\"": "He asks Allah to distinguish between him and the disobedient ones—he doesn't want to share in their punishment. He describes them as fasiqeen (rebellious, sinful), showing his disapproval of their behavior."
  },
  26: {
    "Allah replied, \"Then this land is forbidden to them for forty years,": "As punishment for their refusal, the Holy Land—which was destined for them—was now forbidden to that generation. They had rejected Allah's gift, so Allah withheld it.",
    "during which they will wander through the land.": "For four decades, they wandered lost in the Sinai desert, unable to settle or reach their destination. Every time they tried to find their way, they ended up going in circles. This was a direct consequence of their disobedience.",
    "So do not grieve for the rebellious people.\"": "Allah consoles Moses: don't feel sorry for them. They brought this upon themselves. When people deliberately choose disobedience despite clear guidance, the resulting punishment is their own doing."
  },
  27: {
    "Relate to them in truth ˹O Prophet˺ the story of Adam's two sons—": "Allah commands the Prophet to narrate this true story. Though not named in the Quran, Islamic tradition identifies them as Habil (Abel) and Qabil (Cain). This story carries timeless lessons about jealousy, righteousness, and the consequences of sin.",
    "how each offered a sacrifice:": "Both brothers made offerings to Allah. Habil, a shepherd, offered the best of his flock—a healthy, fat ram. Qabil, a farmer, offered some of his worst crops—low quality produce he didn't want anyway. The quality of what you give to Allah reflects the quality of your faith. When you give charity or make any offering, do you give your best or your leftovers?",
    "Abel's offering was accepted while Cain's was not.": "A fire came from the sky and consumed Habil's sacrifice, indicating acceptance. Qabil's offering remained untouched—a clear sign of rejection. Acceptance depends on sincerity and quality, not just the act itself. Allah looks at your heart and intention, not just the outward action.",
    "So Cain threatened, \"I will kill you!\"": "Instead of reflecting on why his offering was rejected and working to improve himself, Qabil became consumed with jealousy. He blamed his brother for his own failure. This is a common human mistake—when we fail, it's easier to resent those who succeed than to examine our own shortcomings.",
    "His brother replied, \"Allah only accepts ˹the offering˺ of the sincerely devout.": "Habil's response was calm, wise, and instructive. He explained the real reason for the difference: taqwa (God-consciousness and sincerity). Allah doesn't need our sacrifices—He looks for the piety behind them. As Allah says elsewhere: \"Their meat will not reach Allah, nor will their blood, but what reaches Him is piety from you\" (22:37)."
  },
  28: {
    "If you raise your hand to kill me,": "Habil acknowledges the real threat. His brother has made a clear intention to murder him. Yet even in the face of death, Habil remains principled and calm.",
    "I will not raise mine to kill you,": "Habil refuses to respond to violence with equal violence. He will not initiate killing his own brother, even if his life is at stake. Some scholars explain that he refused to be the aggressor or the one who starts the killing. This shows incredible restraint and moral strength. While Islam permits self-defense, Habil chose a higher path—he would not be the one to shed his brother's blood.",
    "because I fear Allah—the Lord of all worlds.": "His reason is profound: fear of Allah. True taqwa means that your consciousness of Allah guides every decision, even in life-threatening situations. Habil would rather face death than commit a sin that would displease His Lord. This is the highest level of faith—when obedience to Allah takes priority over even self-preservation."
  },
  29: {
    "I want to let you bear your sin against me along with your other sins,": "Habil warns his brother about the consequences. If Qabil kills him, Qabil will carry the full burden of sin—not just the murder, but also Habil's potential sins that would have been transferred to him as the victim of oppression. The Prophet (peace be upon him) explained that on the Day of Judgment, the oppressor may have to give their good deeds to the one they oppressed, or take on the victim's sins.",
    "then you will be one of those destined to the Fire.": "Murder, especially of an innocent person, especially of one's own brother, is a fast track to Hell. Habil is giving his brother one final warning about eternal consequences. This isn't a curse—it's a compassionate warning to wake Qabil up before he destroys himself.",
    "And that is the reward of the wrongdoers.\"": "Hellfire is the just compensation for those who wrong others. Habil makes clear that oppression has serious eternal consequences. He has done everything possible to prevent this tragedy—explaining, warning, and refusing to escalate. The responsibility now lies entirely with Qabil."
  },
  30: {
    "Yet Cain convinced himself to kill his brother,": "The word 'tawwa'at' suggests that his soul made the murder seem acceptable, even easy. Sin works this way—it starts as a thought, then the nafs (self) rationalizes it, making the forbidden seem reasonable or even justified. Qabil ignored all the warnings, silenced his conscience, and let jealousy drive him to the unthinkable. Every major sin begins with small compromises and self-justifications.",
    "so he killed him—": "He committed the first murder in human history. He took a life that Allah had made sacred—and not just any life, but his own brother's. This single act introduced homicide into the human experience. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said that Qabil bears a portion of the sin of every murder that occurs until the Day of Judgment, because he was the first to establish this evil practice.",
    "becoming a loser.": "Despite thinking he had won by eliminating his rival, Qabil became the ultimate loser. He lost his brother, his family's trust, his peace of mind, his relationship with Allah, and potentially his eternal soul. The word 'khasireen' (losers) is comprehensive—he lost in every possible way. This is the reality of sin: what seems like gain in the moment always results in tremendous loss."
  },
  31: {
    "Then Allah sent a crow digging ˹a grave˺ in the ground ˹for a dead crow˺,": "This was the first burial in human history. Allah sent a crow—a bird often associated with death—to teach Qabil what to do with the body. One crow dug into the earth and buried another dead crow. This simple act demonstrated the proper way to honor the dead. Even animals, by Allah's guidance, showed more dignity than the murderer knew to show.",
    "in order to show him how to bury the corpse of his brother.": "Qabil had taken a life but didn't know what to do with the body. He had been carrying it around, confused and horrified. The crow became his teacher. There is profound humiliation in this—a human, made as the best of creation, had to learn basic decency from a bird. Sin degrades us below even the animals.",
    "He cried, \"Alas! Have I ˹even˺ failed to be like this crow and bury the corpse of my brother?\"": "Now reality hits him. He expresses frustration at his own inability and ignorance. A mere crow knew what to do while he, a human being, was helpless. This moment of self-awareness shows him how far he has fallen. He couldn't even manage the aftermath of his crime.",
    "So he became regretful.": "Qabil felt nadm (regret)—but was it true repentance? Scholars differ on whether his regret was genuine tawbah (repentance to Allah) or simply remorse over the consequences and his own helplessness. True repentance requires acknowledging the sin, feeling genuine remorse, stopping the sin, and resolving never to return to it. Regret alone, especially regret over getting caught or facing consequences, is not sufficient for forgiveness."
  },
  32: {
    "That is why We ordained for the Children of Israel": "Because of this first murder and its devastating consequences, Allah established a fundamental principle for the Children of Israel (and by extension, for all humanity).",
    "that whoever takes a life—unless as a punishment for murder or mischief in the land—": "Taking a human life is absolutely forbidden except in two cases: legal retribution for murder (carried out by proper authorities, not vigilante justice), or punishment for those who spread serious corruption and violence in society. Outside these narrow exceptions, killing is absolutely prohibited.",
    "it will be as if they killed all of humanity;": "This is one of the most powerful statements in the Quran. When you kill one innocent person, it's as if you've killed everyone. Why? Because you've shown a willingness to violate the sanctity of human life itself. You've attacked the principle that makes human society possible. You've killed the humanity within yourself. Each person is a complete world—with thoughts, relationships, potential, and purpose—and destroying that world is like destroying everything.",
    "and whoever saves a life, it will be as if they saved all of humanity.": "Conversely, saving one life earns the reward of saving all humanity. This includes saving someone from drowning, curing a sick person, feeding the starving, or even guiding someone away from spiritual death through sharing truth. Every life you preserve is an entire universe saved. This should motivate us to value, protect, and preserve human life in every way possible.",
    "˹Although˺ Our messengers already came to them with clear proofs,": "The Children of Israel received this clear guidance through their prophets, with obvious evidence and wisdom.",
    "many of them still transgressed afterwards through the land.": "Despite knowing these principles, many of them continued to commit excesses, including bloodshed and corruption. Knowledge without action is worthless. Knowing that murder is wrong didn't stop people from murdering. This is a warning for all who have knowledge—will you act on what you know?"
  },
  33: {
    "Indeed, the penalty for those who wage war against Allah and His Messenger": "This refers to those who take up arms against the Muslim community, attack travelers, terrorize civilians, or commit armed robbery. \"Waging war against Allah\" doesn't mean literally fighting God—it means fighting against His laws, His people, and the peace He ordained. This includes highway robbers, terrorists, and those who use violence to spread fear.",
    "and spread mischief in the land": "Those who cause fasad (corruption)—killing innocents, terrorizing communities, destroying property, destabilizing society. This isn't about simple crimes but organized violence that threatens public security and order.",
    "is death,": "For the most severe cases, particularly those involving murder, the death penalty is prescribed. This is carried out by the state through proper judicial process, not by individuals.",
    "crucifixion,": "A severe form of public execution used as a strong deterrent for the most heinous crimes that caused multiple deaths or extreme terror.",
    "cutting off their hands and feet on opposite sides,": "For armed robbery without murder—the right hand and left foot, for example. This punishment removes their ability to commit the same crime again and serves as a permanent reminder and deterrent.",
    "or exile from the land.": "For lesser offenses within this category, banishment from their community—imprisonment or deportation—removes them from society so they cannot continue harming people.",
    "This ˹penalty˺ is a disgrace for them in this world,": "These punishments bring public humiliation in this life. They are meant to be severe because the crimes they address are severe—terrorism, armed robbery, and murder cannot be treated lightly. A society must protect its citizens.",
    "and they will suffer a tremendous punishment in the Hereafter.": "Beyond worldly punishment, an even greater punishment awaits in the Hereafter. This shows that human justice, while necessary, is not the end—divine justice is ultimate and complete."
  },
  34: {
    "As for those who repent before you seize them,": "There is an important exception. If someone involved in these crimes sincerely repents and surrenders before being caught, and they repent before the authorities have power over them—",
    "then know that Allah is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful.": "Allah will forgive them, and the prescribed worldly punishment may be waived or reduced. This shows that even for the most serious crimes, the door to repentance remains open. Islam always provides hope and a way back. However, this applies to the rights of Allah—the rights of individual victims (like returning stolen property or compensation for harm) must still be fulfilled."
  },
  35: {
    "O believers! Be mindful of Allah": "The first command is taqwa—consciousness of Allah that leads to obeying Him and avoiding what He prohibited. Taqwa is the foundation of all Islamic practice. It means living with awareness that Allah sees everything you do and will hold you accountable.",
    "and seek what brings you closer to Him": "Wasilah means a means of nearness—anything that brings you closer to Allah. This includes prayer, charity, good deeds, seeking knowledge, dhikr (remembrance of Allah), following the Sunnah, and avoiding sins. Some people misunderstand this to mean seeking intermediaries to pray to, but the Quran itself clarifies that we approach Allah directly through righteous deeds. The wasilah is your own worship and good actions, not calling upon saints or dead people.",
    "and struggle in His Way,": "Jihad here means striving and struggling for Allah's cause. This includes the internal struggle against your own desires (the greater jihad), struggling to establish justice, supporting truth, and when necessary, defending the Muslim community. It encompasses all effort expended to please Allah and establish His deen.",
    "so you may be successful.": "Success (falah) in Islam means achieving good in this world and the Hereafter—salvation, Paradise, and Allah's pleasure. The path to this success is clear: taqwa, seeking nearness to Allah through righteous deeds, and striving in His cause."
  },
  36: {
    "As for the disbelievers, even if they were to possess everything in the world twice over": "Imagine owning every treasure on earth—all the gold, all the wealth, all the resources—and then having double that amount. The richest people in history had only a tiny fraction of this. This hypothetical emphasizes the unimaginable wealth being described.",
    "˹and offer it all˺ to ransom themselves from the punishment of the Day of Judgment,": "Even if they offered all this wealth to escape the punishment of Hell, trying to buy their way out—",
    "it would never be accepted from them.": "Allah would not accept it. There is no price that can purchase salvation on that Day. No wealth, no connections, no status will help. The only currency that matters is faith and righteous deeds, and it's too late to acquire those after death. This is why we must prepare now, while we're alive.",
    "And they will suffer a painful punishment.": "Despite their desperate attempts to escape, they will still face severe punishment. This verse should shake anyone who thinks worldly wealth and success are the ultimate goals. Everything you accumulate will be worthless on that Day if you lack faith."
  },
  37: {
    "They will be desperate to get out of the Fire": "Once in Hell, they will desperately want to escape. Every moment they will wish for a way out. The pain will be unbearable, and they will struggle to leave.",
    "but they will never be able to.": "Their attempts will be futile. Hell is not a place one can escape from. The doors are sealed, and the punishment is decreed. Unlike worldly prisons where sentences end or escapes are possible, Hell for disbelievers is absolute and inescapable.",
    "And they will suffer an everlasting punishment.": "The punishment is muqeem—permanent, established, never-ending. This is the most terrifying aspect: it never stops. No relief, no break, no end in sight—forever. This reality should motivate us to do everything possible to avoid this fate while we still have the chance."
  },
  38: {
    "As for male and female thieves,": "This ruling applies equally to men and women. Islam establishes justice without gender discrimination in legal punishments. Both are held to the same standard of accountability.",
    "cut off their hands": "This is the prescribed punishment for theft. However, Islamic jurisprudence has established strict conditions: the stolen item must be above a minimum value (nisab), it must be taken from a secure place, the thief must be sane and mature, it cannot be out of dire necessity (like stealing bread when starving), and the evidence must be conclusive. These conditions mean this punishment is rarely applicable. Throughout Islamic history, it was seldom implemented because the conditions were so stringent and society provided for the poor.",
    "for what they have done—": "The punishment fits the crime. The hand that was used to unlawfully take others' property is removed. This principle of proportionality ensures that criminals understand the direct consequence of their specific actions.",
    "a deterrent from Allah.": "The purpose is nakalan—a deterrent, a warning to others. When society knows this punishment exists, theft decreases dramatically. The goal is prevention, not revenge. A society that implements Islamic law properly has minimal theft because both the fear of punishment and the social safety net (zakah) work together.",
    "And Allah is Almighty, All-Wise.": "Allah has the power to legislate as He wills, and His legislation is based on perfect wisdom. Even if we don't fully understand the wisdom behind every ruling, we trust that the All-Wise Creator knows what is best for human society."
  },
  39: {
    "But whoever repents after their wrongdoing": "Even after committing theft, the door to repentance is not closed. If a thief genuinely repents—feels remorse, stops stealing, and returns what they stole or compensates the victims—",
    "and mends their ways,": "Repentance must be accompanied by reformation. It's not enough to say \"I'm sorry\"—you must actually change your behavior and make things right. True tawbah involves correcting the wrong as much as possible.",
    "Allah will surely turn to them in forgiveness.": "Allah accepts sincere repentance. His forgiveness is available even for serious crimes. This repentance may affect the worldly punishment (if the victim forgives and the property is returned before the case reaches the judge), and it certainly affects the Hereafter—a sincere repentant person is not punished again for the same sin.",
    "Indeed, Allah is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful.": "Allah's forgiveness is vast and His mercy encompasses all things. No sin is too great for His forgiveness if the repentance is sincere. This ending on a note of mercy balances the severity of the punishment, reminding us that Islam combines justice with compassion."
  },
  40: {
    "Do you not know that the kingdom of the heavens and the earth belongs to Allah ˹alone˺?": "This is a rhetorical question meant to remind and affirm a fundamental truth. Allah owns everything—every star, every planet, every atom, and every soul. Nothing exists outside His dominion. When you truly understand this, you realize that all power, all authority, and all decisions ultimately rest with Him alone.",
    "He punishes whoever He wills": "Allah has the absolute right to punish anyone He chooses based on His perfect wisdom and justice. His punishment is never arbitrary—it is always deserved by those who earn it through their rejection of truth and persistence in sin.",
    "and forgives whoever He wills.": "Similarly, Allah forgives whomever He chooses. His forgiveness is vast and available to anyone who sincerely repents. This balance of punishment and forgiveness reflects His attributes of justice and mercy working together.",
    "And Allah is Most Capable of everything.": "There is absolutely nothing beyond Allah's power. He can punish, He can forgive, He can create, He can destroy—all with perfect ease. This should inspire both hope in His mercy and fear of His punishment."
  },
  41: {
    "O Messenger! Do not grieve for those who race to disbelieve—": "Allah addresses His beloved Prophet with this special title, showing honor and intimacy. The Prophet (peace be upon him) deeply cared about guiding people and was pained when he saw people rushing toward disbelief. Allah consoles him: don't let their choices break your heart. You cannot force guidance upon anyone.",
    "those who say, \"We believe\" with their tongues, but their hearts are in disbelief.": "These are the hypocrites—people who claim Islam outwardly but harbor rejection in their hearts. They are more dangerous than open enemies because they appear as friends while working against the community from within. The Prophet dealt with many such individuals in Madinah.",
    "Nor those among the Jews who eagerly listen to lies,": "Some Jews in Madinah would readily accept and spread falsehoods about the Prophet and Islam. They weren't interested in truth; they actively sought out lies that suited their agenda.",
    "attentive to those who are too arrogant to come to you.": "They acted as spies and informants for other Jewish leaders who were too proud to come to the Prophet themselves. These absent leaders wanted to know what rulings the Prophet would give so they could cherry-pick what suited them.",
    "They distort the Scripture, taking rulings out of context,": "They would change the meanings of their own Torah, twisting words and interpretations to suit their desires. This distortion (tahrif) involved taking verses out of their proper context to justify whatever they wanted.",
    "then say, \"If this is the ruling you get ˹from Muhammad˺, accept it. If not, beware!\"": "Their approach to the Prophet was purely opportunistic. If his ruling matched what they wanted, they would accept it as validation. If not, they would reject it and warn others not to follow it. They weren't seeking truth; they were seeking confirmation of their preferences.",
    "Whoever Allah allows to be deluded, you can never be of any help to them against Allah.": "When someone persistently chooses misguidance, Allah may seal that choice. At that point, even the Prophet (peace be upon him) cannot help them. This shows that guidance ultimately comes from Allah, and those who reject it repeatedly may lose access to it.",
    "It is not Allah's Will to purify their hearts.": "Because of their constant rejection and corruption, Allah has not willed to cleanse their hearts from disbelief and hypocrisy. This is a consequence of their own choices, not arbitrary punishment.",
    "For them there is disgrace in this world,": "They will face humiliation and exposure in this life. Their schemes will be uncovered, their reputation will be ruined, and they will be known for their treachery.",
    "and they will suffer a tremendous punishment in the Hereafter.": "Beyond worldly disgrace, an immense punishment awaits them in the Hereafter. This dual consequence—shame now and torment later—is the fate of those who deliberately choose deception over truth."
  },
  42: {
    "They eagerly listen to falsehood": "They are habitual consumers of lies—they seek out false information and rumors, preferring them to truth.",
    "and consume forbidden gain.": "They also eat wealth obtained through unlawful means—bribery, usury, theft, or other prohibited transactions. This combination of loving lies and consuming haram wealth shows complete moral corruption.",
    "So if they come to you ˹O Prophet˺, either judge between them or turn away from them.": "Allah gives the Prophet a choice when these people bring their disputes to him. He can either judge their case or refuse to get involved. This flexibility was given because of their insincerity—they weren't genuinely seeking justice.",
    "If you turn away from them, they cannot harm you whatsoever.": "If you choose not to judge their case, don't worry—they have no power to harm you. Allah protects His Messenger, so there's no need to fear their reaction.",
    "But if you judge between them, then do so with justice.": "However, if you do choose to judge, you must be completely fair—even toward enemies, even toward hypocrites, even toward those who don't deserve kindness. Justice is non-negotiable in Islam.",
    "Surely Allah loves those who are just.": "This beautiful statement should motivate every believer. Being just earns Allah's love. When you treat people fairly—regardless of who they are—you become beloved to your Creator."
  },
  43: {
    "But why do they come to you for judgment": "Allah expresses amazement at their behavior. Why would they seek your judgment when they claim their own scripture is sufficient?",
    "when they ˹already˺ have the Torah containing Allah's judgment,": "The Torah, which they claim to follow, already has Allah's rulings on these matters. If they truly believed in it, they would follow it.",
    "then they turn away after all?": "Even when they come to the Prophet and receive a ruling, they reject it if it doesn't match their desires. This proves they were never seeking truth—just validation.",
    "They are not ˹true˺ believers.": "Their behavior exposes their lack of genuine faith. True believers accept Allah's judgment whether it favors them or not. These people only wanted rulings that suited their interests."
  },
  44: {
    "Indeed, We revealed the Torah, containing guidance and light,": "Allah affirms that He revealed the Torah as a source of guidance and illumination for the Children of Israel. It was a genuine revelation meant to guide people to truth and righteousness.",
    "by which the prophets, who submitted themselves to Allah, made judgments for Jews.": "All the prophets who came after Moses—including David, Solomon, and others—judged according to the Torah. They were all Muslims in the sense that they submitted to Allah (which is what 'Islam' means). They used the Torah to settle disputes and guide their people.",
    "So too did the rabbis and scholars judge according to Allah's Book,": "Religious scholars and rabbis were also supposed to judge by the Torah. They were entrusted with preserving and implementing Allah's law among their communities.",
    "with which they were entrusted and of which they were made keepers.": "Allah entrusted them with His Book. They were responsible for protecting it from corruption and ensuring it was properly implemented. This was a sacred trust.",
    "So do not fear the people; fear Me!": "A powerful command: your fear should be of Allah, not of what people might think or do. Many scholars compromise truth to please powerful people or avoid controversy. This is forbidden.",
    "Nor trade my revelations for a fleeting gain.": "Don't sell out Allah's truth for worldly benefits—money, status, or popularity. Some rabbis would change rulings for bribes or to please the wealthy. Any worldly gain is \"fleeting\" compared to what you lose in the Hereafter.",
    "And those who do not judge by what Allah has revealed are ˹truly˺ the disbelievers.": "Those who deliberately reject and refuse to judge by Allah's law—while having access to it and recognizing its truth—have fallen into disbelief. This is a severe warning about abandoning divine law for personal preferences or other systems."
  },
  45: {
    "We ordained for them in the Torah, \"A life for a life,": "This establishes the principle of equal retribution. If someone deliberately kills another person, the killer's life may be taken in return. This is not about revenge but about justice and the value of human life.",
    "an eye for an eye,": "If someone causes someone to lose an eye, the same can be done to them. This ensures that punishment matches the crime—no more, no less.",
    "a nose for a nose, an ear for an ear, a tooth for a tooth—": "The principle extends to all physical injuries. The punishment is proportional to the harm caused. This prevents both excessive punishment and inadequate consequences.",
    "and for wounds equal retaliation.\"": "For any injury, there is proportional retaliation. This law establishes fairness and prevents cycles of excessive revenge where one injury leads to greater counter-injury.",
    "But whoever waives it charitably, it will be atonement for them.": "Here Islam introduces mercy into justice. The victim (or their family) has the right to forgive and forgo retaliation. If they do so as an act of charity, it becomes expiation for their own sins. The Prophet (peace be upon him) encouraged forgiveness when possible.",
    "And those who do not judge by what Allah has revealed are ˹truly˺ the wrongdoers.": "Those who refuse to implement Allah's justice system—whether by punishing too harshly or too leniently based on personal preferences—are oppressors. True justice comes only from following divine guidance."
  },
  46: {
    "Then in the footsteps of the prophets, We sent Jesus, son of Mary,": "Jesus (peace be upon him) came in the line of prophets that came before him. He was not a break from tradition but a continuation of the prophetic mission. He is identified by his mother because he had no father—a miraculous birth.",
    "confirming the Torah revealed before him.": "Jesus didn't come to abolish the Torah but to confirm and uphold its essential teachings. He affirmed the law of Moses while bringing some new guidance specific to his mission.",
    "And We gave him the Gospel containing guidance and light": "Allah gave Jesus the Injeel (Gospel)—a scripture with the same purpose as the Torah: to guide people and illuminate their path to Allah. The original Gospel was divine revelation, though what exists today has been altered.",
    "and confirming what was revealed in the Torah—": "The Gospel reinforced the Torah's core message of monotheism, righteousness, and preparing for the final Prophet.",
    "a guide and a lesson to the God-fearing.": "The Gospel served as guidance for those who had taqwa—consciousness of Allah. Scriptures benefit those who approach them with sincere hearts seeking truth."
  },
  47: {
    "So let the people of the Gospel judge by what Allah has revealed in it.": "Christians were commanded to follow the true teachings of the Gospel given to Jesus. They should have judged their affairs according to its authentic guidance.",
    "And those who do not judge by what Allah has revealed are ˹truly˺ the rebellious.": "Notice the progression: verse 44 called them 'disbelievers,' verse 45 called them 'wrongdoers,' and now verse 47 calls them 'rebellious' (fasiqun). All these describe the severity of abandoning divine law, with slightly different emphases on the nature of the transgression."
  },
  48: {
    "We have revealed to you ˹O Prophet˺ this Book with the truth,": "The Quran is described as being revealed with truth—it is true in its origin (from Allah), true in its content (no falsehood in it), and true in its purpose (guiding to truth).",
    "as a confirmation of previous Scriptures": "Like the Gospel confirmed the Torah, the Quran confirms the essential truths of all previous revelations. The core message of monotheism and righteousness remains consistent.",
    "and a supreme authority on them.": "The Quran is muhaymin—a guardian, protector, and judge over previous scriptures. It confirms what was authentic in them, corrects what was distorted, and abrogates what was meant to be temporary. When there's any conflict, the Quran has the final word.",
    "So judge between them by what Allah has revealed,": "The Prophet is commanded to use the Quran as the basis for all judgments. This establishes Islamic law as the standard for the Muslim community.",
    "and do not follow their desires over the truth that has come to you.": "Don't let people's preferences, pressures, or demands cause you to deviate from Quranic guidance. People will always try to get rulings that favor them; resist this pressure.",
    "To each of you We have ordained a code of law and a way of life.": "Different prophets and communities received different specific laws (shariah) and methodologies (minhaj) suited to their times and circumstances. The fundamentals remained the same, but some details varied.",
    "If Allah had willed, He would have made you one community,": "Allah could have made everyone follow exactly the same rules from the beginning, but He chose diversity for a purpose.",
    "but His Will is to test you with what He has given ˹each of˺ you.": "The differences serve as a test. Will you follow what Allah has given you? Will you respect others while maintaining your own guidance? Will you seek truth despite challenges?",
    "So compete with one another in doing good.": "Instead of fighting over differences, compete in righteousness. Try to outdo each other in good deeds, charity, and worship. This positive competition benefits everyone.",
    "To Allah you will all return,": "Regardless of your community or background, everyone returns to Allah for final judgment.",
    "then He will inform you ˹of the truth˺ regarding your differences.": "All disputes about religion will be settled by Allah on the Day of Judgment. He will clarify who was right and who was wrong. Until then, focus on doing good."
  },
  49: {
    "And judge between them ˹O Prophet˺ by what Allah has revealed,": "This command is repeated for emphasis. Divine revelation must be the basis of all judgments—no exceptions, no compromises.",
    "and do not follow their desires.": "Again, the warning against being swayed by what people want rather than what Allah has decreed. Human desires are often misguided; divine guidance is always perfect.",
    "And beware, so they do not lure you away from some of what Allah has revealed to you.": "Be extremely cautious! People may try to convince you to modify or ignore certain rulings. They might use persuasion, pressure, or deception. Even compromising on a small part of revelation is dangerous.",
    "If they turn away ˹from Allah's judgment˺, then know that it is Allah's Will to repay them for some of their sins,": "When people reject divine guidance, Allah may punish them as a consequence of their accumulated sins. Their rejection itself brings punishment upon them.",
    "and that many people are indeed rebellious.": "This is the sad reality—many people are fasiqun (rebellious transgressors). Don't be surprised when people reject truth; it has always been this way."
  },
  50: {
    "Is it the judgment of ˹pre-Islamic˺ ignorance they seek?": "Do they want to return to the chaotic, unjust systems of jahiliyyah (the age of ignorance before Islam)? That era was marked by oppression, tribalism, and the strong exploiting the weak. Any system that deviates from divine law shares these characteristics.",
    "Who could be a better judge than Allah for people of sure faith?": "This rhetorical question has an obvious answer: no one. For those who truly believe, there is no question that Allah's judgment is superior to any human system. His laws are based on perfect knowledge, absolute justice, and complete wisdom."
  },
  51: {
    "O believers! Take neither Jews nor Christians as guardians—": "This verse addresses a specific type of relationship: wilayah (guardianship, alliance, or intimate political loyalty). It does not forbid normal interactions, business dealings, or kind treatment. Rather, it warns against giving your ultimate loyalty and allegiance to those who oppose your faith. Muslims must not take those hostile to Islam as their protectors or closest allies against other Muslims.",
    "they are guardians of each other.": "Jews and Christians, despite their differences with each other, will ultimately unite when it comes to opposing Islam. Their religious and political loyalties ultimately exclude Muslims. This was demonstrated historically and continues to be relevant.",
    "Whoever does so will be counted as one of them.": "If a Muslim gives their complete loyalty to those who are hostile to Islam—choosing them over fellow Muslims—they become associated with them. This is a severe warning about where misplaced loyalty leads.",
    "Surely Allah does not guide the wrongdoing people.": "Those who wrong themselves by abandoning their community for those who oppose it will not receive Allah's guidance. Their choice leads them further from truth."
  },
  52: {
    "You see those with sickness in their hearts": "This refers to the hypocrites—those whose faith is weak or insincere. Their hearts are diseased with doubt, fear, and lack of trust in Allah.",
    "racing for their guardianship,": "They rush to form alliances with Jews and Christians, seeking their protection and favor. They compete to show loyalty to them.",
    "saying ˹in justification˺, \"We fear a turn of fortune will strike us.\"": "Their excuse is pragmatic fear: \"What if the Muslims lose? What if circumstances change? We need backup plans.\" They hedge their bets instead of trusting Allah.",
    "But perhaps Allah will bring about ˹your˺ victory": "Allah may grant the Muslims a decisive victory that will prove these hypocrites' fears were unfounded.",
    "or another favour by His command,": "Or Allah may bring some other development that exposes the hypocrites and vindicates the believers.",
    "and they will regret what they have hidden in their hearts.": "When Allah's help comes, these hypocrites will deeply regret their secret disloyalty. Their hidden treachery will be exposed, and they will have neither the Muslims' trust nor the protection they sought from others."
  },
  53: {
    "˹Only then,˺ the believers will ask ˹one another˺, \"Are these the ones who swore solemn oaths by Allah that they were with you?\"": "When the hypocrites are exposed, the true believers will be amazed. These were people who swore the strongest oaths that they were committed Muslims, loyal to the community. Their exposure reveals the emptiness of their claims.",
    "Their deeds have been in vain,": "Whatever good deeds they performed have been nullified by their hypocrisy. Just as a building collapses when its foundation is rotten, their actions became worthless because they were built on insincerity.",
    "so they have become losers.": "They lost everything—respect in this world, and reward in the Hereafter. They tried to have it both ways and ended up with nothing."
  },
  54: {
    "O believers! Whoever among you abandons their faith,": "This is a direct warning about apostasy—leaving Islam after having accepted it. It's a severe sin with serious consequences.",
    "Allah will replace them with others": "Allah's religion does not depend on any individual or group. If some leave, Allah will bring others who are better and more sincere. Islam doesn't need anyone; people need Islam.",
    "who love Him and are loved by Him.": "The replacement group will have a mutual love relationship with Allah—they love Him sincerely, and He loves them in return. This is the highest honor and the essence of true faith.",
    "They will be humble with the believers": "Toward fellow believers, they are gentle, compassionate, and easy-going. They don't act arrogantly toward their brothers and sisters in faith. True strength shows as gentleness toward friends.",
    "but firm towards the disbelievers,": "Toward those hostile to Islam, they are strong and unyielding. They don't compromise their principles or show weakness when facing enemies of the faith. This isn't about being mean to individuals but about being principled.",
    "struggling in the Way of Allah;": "They actively work for Allah's cause—through effort, resources, time, and if necessary, their lives. They don't just claim faith; they live it.",
    "fearing no blame from anyone.": "They do what's right regardless of criticism. People might mock them, criticize them, or blame them for standing firm on truth—but they don't care. Allah's approval matters more than any human opinion.",
    "This is the favour of Allah. He grants it to whoever He wills.": "These beautiful qualities are a gift from Allah. You should ask Him for them and strive to develop them, but ultimately they come through His grace.",
    "And Allah is All-Bountiful, All-Knowing.": "Allah's bounty is vast—He can transform anyone into a beloved servant. And He knows who deserves this honor and who is sincere in seeking it."
  },
  55: {
    "Your only guardians are Allah, His Messenger, and fellow believers—": "This definitively answers the question of where a Muslim's ultimate loyalty should lie. Your wali (guardian, protector, ally) is Allah first, then His Messenger, then the community of believers. This is your support system.",
    "who establish prayer": "True believers are identified by their consistent prayer. They don't just occasionally pray; they establish it as a regular, well-performed act of worship.",
    "and pay alms-tax with humility.": "They also pay zakah (mandatory charity) not grudgingly but with humble, willing hearts. The phrase \"while they bow\" (wa hum raki'un) indicates their constant state of submission and humility—they give while in a state of devotion to Allah."
  },
  56: {
    "Whoever allies themselves with Allah, His Messenger, and fellow believers,": "When you make Allah, His Messenger, and the believers your true allies and supporters—",
    "then it is certainly Allah's party that will prevail.": "You become part of \"Hizbullah\"—the Party of Allah. And Allah's party is always ultimately victorious. This doesn't mean they never face hardship, but that final success belongs to them. This is a tremendous promise and encouragement."
  },
  57: {
    "O believers! Do not seek the guardianship of those given the Scripture before you and the disbelievers": "This expands the previous warning. Don't take as close allies those from the People of the Book or other disbelievers who show hostility to your faith.",
    "who have made your faith a mockery and amusement.": "Specifically, avoid those who ridicule Islam—who treat your prayers, fasting, hijab, or beliefs as jokes. People who mock what you hold sacred should not be your intimate friends or trusted allies.",
    "And be mindful of Allah if you are ˹truly˺ believers.": "If you truly have faith, you will protect it by choosing your associations carefully. Your taqwa should guide who you allow to influence you."
  },
  58: {
    "When you call to prayer, they mock it in amusement.": "The adhan (call to prayer)—one of the most beautiful and significant symbols of Islam—they treat as a joke. They laugh at it, make fun of it, or mock those who respond to it.",
    "This is because they are a people without understanding.": "Their mockery reveals their ignorance and lack of intellect. A truly intelligent person respects others' sincere worship even if they don't share the faith. Mocking sacred practices shows shallow thinking and spiritual blindness."
  },
  59: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"O People of the Book! Do you resent us only because we believe in Allah": "The Prophet is instructed to challenge them directly. What exactly is your problem with us? Is it that we believe in God?",
    "and what has been revealed to us": "We believe in the Quran that was revealed to our Prophet.",
    "and what was revealed before—": "We also believe in your scriptures—the Torah and Gospel in their original forms. So we're not rejecting your prophets; we're accepting more than you do!",
    "while most of you are rebellious?\"": "The real issue is that most of them have strayed from true religion, and our faith exposes their deviation. They resent us for following truth that they abandoned."
  },
  60: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Shall I inform you of those who deserve a worse punishment from Allah ˹than the rebellious˺?": "Let me tell you about people who are in far worse condition than those you criticize.",
    "It is those who earned Allah's condemnation and displeasure—": "These are people upon whom Allah's curse and anger descended because of their persistent wickedness.",
    "some being reduced to apes and pigs": "Some among their ancestors were transformed into apes and pigs as punishment for their violations, particularly breaking the Sabbath. This refers to a historical event mentioned elsewhere in the Quran.",
    "and worshippers of false gods.": "And some fell into idol worship, abandoning the monotheism their prophets taught.",
    "These are far worse in rank": "These people are in a much worse position than those they criticize.",
    "and farther astray from the Right Way.\"": "They have strayed much further from truth than the Muslims they resent. Before criticizing others, they should examine their own history and current state."
  },
  61: {
    "When they come to you ˹believers˺ they say, \"We believe.\"": "When meeting Muslims, these hypocrites claim to be believers. They speak the words of faith.",
    "But they are committed to disbelief when they enter and when they leave.": "But they entered as disbelievers and leave as disbelievers. Their hearts never changed; only their words did. Their declaration of faith is completely hollow.",
    "And Allah knows what they hide.": "They might fool people with their words, but Allah knows exactly what's in their hearts. Nothing is hidden from Him."
  },
  62: {
    "You see many of them racing towards sin, transgression,": "They compete in committing sins and violating rights. It's not occasional mistakes—they actively pursue wrongdoing.",
    "and consumption of forbidden gain.": "They eagerly consume haram income—bribes, usury, stolen goods, and other unlawful earnings.",
    "Evil indeed are their actions!": "Allah explicitly condemns their behavior. What they do is wicked and deserving of punishment."
  },
  63: {
    "Why do their rabbis and scholars not forbid them from saying what is sinful": "This is a serious indictment of religious leadership. The scholars and rabbis who should have corrected these people remained silent.",
    "and consuming what is unlawful?": "They didn't speak against the haram income being consumed. They failed in their responsibility to enjoin good and forbid evil.",
    "Evil indeed is their inaction!": "Notice: the previous verse condemned the evil actions of the sinners; this verse condemns the inaction of the scholars. Both are blameworthy. Scholars who fail to speak truth are accomplices to the sins they could have prevented. This is a warning to religious leaders in every age."
  },
  64: {
    "˹Some among˺ the Jews said, \"Allah is tight-fisted.\"": "When they experienced hardship or saw others prospering, some Jews blasphemously claimed that Allah was stingy and withheld blessings. This is a terrible statement that denies Allah's generosity.",
    "May their fists be tied and they be condemned for what they said.": "Allah responds to their insult with a curse upon them. They accused Allah of being tight-fisted, so may their own hands be bound and restricted. This is a fitting response to their blasphemy.",
    "Rather, He is open-handed, giving freely as He pleases.": "The truth is the exact opposite of their claim. Allah's hands are open with generosity. He gives abundantly to whomever He wills. All provision, blessings, and mercy flow from His boundless generosity.",
    "That which has been revealed to you ˹O Prophet˺ from your Lord will only cause many of them to increase in wickedness and disbelief.": "Tragically, the more revelation they receive, the more some of them reject it. The Quran, which should guide them to truth, becomes a source of increased rebellion for those whose hearts are sealed.",
    "We have stirred among them hostility and hatred until the Day of Judgment.": "As a consequence of their rejection, Allah has placed enmity between their various factions. They remain divided, fighting among themselves. This disunity is both punishment and proof of their deviation.",
    "Whenever they kindle the fire of war, Allah puts it out.": "They repeatedly try to conspire against the Muslims and start conflicts, but Allah foils their plots. Their schemes consistently fail because they're working against Allah's plan.",
    "And they strive to spread corruption in the land.": "They work to cause mischief, disorder, and harm on earth—disrupting peace and justice wherever they can.",
    "And Allah does not like corruptors.": "Allah has no love for those who spread corruption. They earn His displeasure and eventual punishment."
  },
  65: {
    "Had the People of the Book only been faithful and mindful ˹of Allah˺,": "If the Jews and Christians had truly believed in Allah and all His messengers (including Muhammad, peace be upon him) and maintained consciousness of Him—",
    "We would have certainly absolved them of their sins": "Allah would have forgiven all their previous sins. The door to forgiveness was always open to them.",
    "and admitted them into the Gardens of Bliss.": "They would have earned Paradise with all its pleasures. This shows that Allah's offer of mercy extends to everyone who accepts it."
  },
  66: {
    "And had they observed the Torah, the Gospel, and what has been revealed to them from their Lord,": "If they had genuinely followed their scriptures—which pointed to the coming of Muhammad and commanded obedience to all prophets—",
    "they would have been overwhelmed with provisions from above and below.": "Blessings would have poured upon them from every direction—rain from the sky, crops from the earth, and every form of provision. Following divine guidance brings material as well as spiritual blessings.",
    "Some among them are upright,": "To be fair, not all of them are the same. Some among the People of the Book are moderate, righteous people who try to follow truth sincerely.",
    "yet many do nothing but evil.": "However, the majority of them engage in evil deeds. They have strayed far from the teachings of their own prophets."
  },
  67: {
    "O Messenger! Convey everything revealed to you from your Lord.": "The Prophet is commanded to deliver the entire message without holding anything back. Whether it's easy or difficult, popular or unpopular, everything must be conveyed. There can be no selective preaching.",
    "If you do not, then you have not delivered His message.": "Withholding even part of the revelation would mean failing in the prophetic mission entirely. The message must be complete. This also confirms that the Prophet (peace be upon him) did deliver everything—nothing was hidden or lost.",
    "Allah will ˹certainly˺ protect you from the people.": "The Prophet might have feared for his safety when delivering certain challenging messages. Allah assures him of divine protection. He need not fear any human—Allah will guard him from harm.",
    "Indeed, Allah does not guide the people who disbelieve.": "Those who insist on disbelief will not be guided. The Prophet's job is only to convey; guidance is from Allah, and it won't come to those who determinedly reject it."
  },
  68: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"O People of the Book! You have nothing to stand on": "Your claim to religion means nothing. You have no valid religious standing.",
    "unless you observe the Torah, the Gospel, and what has been revealed to you from your Lord.\"": "Only by following all of divine revelation—including the Quran, which was revealed to you through Prophet Muhammad—can you truly practice what your scriptures taught. True Judaism and Christianity, properly understood, lead to accepting Muhammad (peace be upon him).",
    "And your Lord's revelation to you ˹O Prophet˺ will only cause many of them to increase in wickedness and disbelief.": "The sad reality is repeated: many of them will respond to the Quran not with acceptance but with increased rejection. The more truth they receive, the more some rebel against it.",
    "So do not grieve for the people who disbelieve.": "Allah again consoles His Prophet. Don't let their rejection break your heart. You've done your duty; their choices are on them."
  },
  69: {
    "Indeed, the believers, Jews, Sabians and Christians—": "This verse mentions various religious groups to make an inclusive point about who can attain salvation.",
    "whoever ˹truly˺ believes in Allah and the Last Day and does good,": "The condition for salvation is genuine faith in Allah (as He truly is, not with distortions), belief in the Day of Judgment (with all its accountability), and performing righteous deeds. This is the universal standard.",
    "there will be no fear for them, nor will they grieve.": "Those who meet these conditions—regardless of what label they previously carried—will have nothing to fear on the Day of Judgment and no grief over what they left behind. This verse applies to those who, in every era, followed the true guidance available to them, including accepting Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) when his message reached them."
  },
  70: {
    "Indeed, We took a covenant from the Children of Israel": "Allah made a binding agreement with them, establishing their responsibilities and His promises.",
    "and sent them messengers.": "Prophet after prophet was sent to guide them and remind them of their covenant.",
    "Whenever a messenger came to them with what they did not desire,": "The problem was that prophets brought messages that challenged their desires and comfortable sins. True prophecy often demands change.",
    "they denied some": "Some prophets they rejected and called liars, refusing to follow their guidance.",
    "and killed others.": "Other prophets they actually murdered. This is an extreme level of rejection—not just disbelieving the message but killing the messenger. The prophets Zechariah and John (Yahya) are traditionally understood to have been killed by Israelites."
  },
  71: {
    "They thought there would be no consequences,": "They assumed they could kill prophets and reject messages without any repercussions. They felt immune to punishment.",
    "so they turned a blind eye and a deaf ear.": "They deliberately chose not to see the truth and not to hear the warnings. Their blindness and deafness were willful.",
    "Yet Allah turned to them in forgiveness ˹after their repentance˺,": "Despite their sins, when they repented, Allah accepted their repentance and forgave them. This shows His immense mercy.",
    "but again many became blind and deaf.": "Tragically, they repeated the cycle. Even after experiencing forgiveness, many of them returned to their old ways of rejecting truth.",
    "And Allah is All-Seeing of what they do.": "Nothing escapes Allah's observation. He sees every act of obedience and every act of rebellion, and He will hold everyone accountable."
  },
  72: {
    "Those who say, \"Allah is the Messiah, son of Mary,\" have certainly fallen into disbelief.": "Claiming that Jesus is God is kufr (disbelief). This directly contradicts the essence of monotheism. Jesus (peace be upon him) was a great prophet, not a deity.",
    "The Messiah ˹himself˺ said, \"O Children of Israel! Worship Allah—my Lord and your Lord.\"": "Jesus himself clarified his status. He called Allah \"my Lord\"—indicating he was a servant of Allah, not Allah Himself. He directed worship to Allah, not to himself. His message was consistent with all prophets: worship the One God.",
    "Whoever associates others with Allah ˹in worship˺ will surely be forbidden Paradise by Allah.": "Shirk (associating partners with Allah) is the unforgivable sin if one dies upon it. Those who commit it are barred from Paradise.",
    "Their home will be the Fire.": "Instead of Paradise, they will dwell in Hell—a terrible consequence for a terrible error.",
    "And the wrongdoers will have no helpers.": "On the Day of Judgment, those who committed shirk will find no one to help them. No intercessor will avail them against Allah's judgment."
  },
  73: {
    "Those who say, \"Allah is one in a Trinity,\" have certainly fallen into disbelief.": "The doctrine of Trinity—that God is three persons in one—is also declared to be disbelief. This concept was developed centuries after Jesus and contradicts pure monotheism.",
    "There is only One God.": "Allah states the simple, clear truth: there is only one God, not three, not two—one. This is the foundation of all true religion from Adam to Muhammad.",
    "If they do not stop saying this,": "A warning: if they continue upon this false belief—",
    "those who disbelieve among them will be afflicted with a painful punishment.": "They will face severe punishment. The door to repentance is still open, but those who persist will face consequences."
  },
  74: {
    "Will they not turn to Allah in repentance": "Despite the severity of their error, the door remains open. Allah asks: why don't they just repent? It's not too late.",
    "and seek His forgiveness?": "They can still ask for forgiveness. Allah is calling them back, even after describing their disbelief.",
    "And Allah is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful.": "No matter how grave the sin—even shirk—Allah will forgive those who sincerely repent before death. His forgiveness is vast, and His mercy encompasses all who turn back to Him."
  },
  75: {
    "The Messiah, son of Mary, was no more than a messenger.": "Jesus's true status is clearly defined: he was a messenger—noble, honored, and beloved by Allah, but still a human messenger, not a god.",
    "˹Many˺ messengers had ˹come and˺ gone before him.": "He was part of a long line of prophets. There was nothing unique about his status as a messenger—many came before him with the same mission of calling to Allah.",
    "His mother was a woman of truth.": "Mary (Maryam) is honored as a siddiqah—a woman of complete truthfulness and devotion. She is among the greatest women ever, but still a human being, not divine.",
    "They both ate food.": "This simple fact is profound evidence against their divinity. Both Jesus and Mary ate food. Gods don't need to eat. Anyone who eats, digests, and eliminates waste is clearly a dependent creature, not the self-sufficient Creator. This logical argument is accessible to anyone who thinks about it.",
    "See how We make the signs clear to them,": "Allah presents clear proofs, simple logic, and obvious evidence.",
    "yet see how they are deluded ˹from the truth˺!": "Despite the clarity of these signs, many remain blind to the truth. Their delusion is by choice, not by lack of evidence."
  },
  76: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"How can you worship besides Allah those who can neither harm nor benefit you?": "A challenge to think rationally: why worship something that has no power to hurt you or help you? What's the point of directing worship to the powerless? Whether it's Jesus, Mary, saints, idols, or any other creation—none of them can independently cause you any harm or bring you any benefit. They are all dependent on Allah just like you are. Worship should be directed to the One who actually controls all affairs.",
    "And Allah ˹alone˺ is the All-Hearing, All-Knowing.\"": "In contrast, Allah hears every prayer and knows every need. He alone has the power to respond. When you call upon Him, He hears you. When you need something, He knows it even before you ask. Direct your worship to the One who can actually answer. This verse uses simple logic to dismantle the basis of all forms of shirk (associating partners with Allah)."
  },
  77: {
    "Say, \"O People of the Book! Do not go to extremes in your faith beyond the truth,": "Religious extremism—going beyond proper bounds—is condemned in Islam. The Christians went to extremes regarding Jesus, elevating him from a noble prophet to God or the son of God. They also elevated Mary and saints to positions of worship. The Jews, in contrast, went to the opposite extreme—rejecting prophets entirely, even trying to kill them, and belittling Jesus and his mother. Both forms of extremism are wrong. True religion is balanced—honoring prophets without worshipping them, following divine law without adding or subtracting from it.",
    "nor follow the vain desires of those who went astray before ˹you˺.": "Don't follow the misguided paths of previous generations who strayed from truth. Their errors should serve as warnings, not examples to imitate. Many of the doctrines that Christians follow today—like the Trinity—were developed by people who had already gone astray from the pure monotheism of Jesus. Following their desires rather than divine guidance led them into error.",
    "They misled many": "Those who deviated from truth didn't just harm themselves—they led countless others astray. Religious leaders who innovate false doctrines bear the sin of everyone they mislead. This is why spreading misguidance is such a serious matter. False teachings spread like diseases, infecting generations.",
    "and strayed from the Right Way.\"": "They completely departed from sawa' as-sabeel—the straight, middle, balanced path. This is the path of all prophets: pure monotheism, worship of Allah alone, following divine guidance without addition or subtraction. Every prophet from Adam to Muhammad (peace be upon them all) walked this same straight path."
  },
  78: {
    "The disbelievers among the Children of Israel were condemned": "Not all of the Children of Israel were condemned—only those who disbelieved and rejected guidance. Allah's curse fell upon specific individuals and groups who chose to rebel against Him.",
    "in the revelations of David and Jesus, son of Mary.": "This curse came through their own prophets—David in the Psalms (Zabur) and Jesus in the Gospel (Injeel). Their own scriptures recorded divine condemnation of those among them who transgressed. This shows that the warning wasn't something new brought by Muhammad (peace be upon him); it was already in their own books.",
    "That was for their disobedience and violations.": "The reason for the curse is clearly stated: they disobeyed Allah's commands and transgressed His limits. They knew what was right but deliberately chose to do wrong. Their punishment was a direct consequence of their choices, not arbitrary divine anger."
  },
  79: {
    "They did not forbid one another from doing evil.": "This is a critical point: their sin wasn't just that individuals did wrong, but that the community as a whole stopped commanding good and forbidding evil. When someone committed a sin, others didn't object or try to stop them. They abandoned the collective responsibility of enjoining good and forbidding evil (amr bil ma'roof wa nahi 'an al-munkar). The Prophet (peace be upon him) warned that when people see wrong and don't try to change it, Allah's punishment may encompass all of them—both the sinners and those who remained silent.",
    "Evil indeed was what they did!": "Allah expresses strong condemnation of their behavior. Both the sins they committed and their failure to stop each other are condemned. A righteous community must actively work to maintain its moral standards. Silence in the face of evil is itself a form of evil. When good people do nothing, evil flourishes."
  },
  80: {
    "You see many of them taking the disbelievers as allies.": "Another serious transgression: many among the People of the Book allied themselves with pagans and disbelievers against the Muslims. They preferred the friendship and support of idol-worshippers over those who actually shared their belief in One God and the prophets. This is a betrayal of their own faith's principles. They put worldly interests and tribal loyalties above religious solidarity.",
    "Truly wicked are their misdeeds,": "What they sent forward for themselves—their record of deeds—is evil. On the Day of Judgment, these actions will be presented against them. They prepared their own destruction through their choices.",
    "which have earned them Allah's wrath.": "Allah is angry with them because of their choices. Divine anger is not arbitrary—it is a direct response to deliberate, persistent sin and betrayal.",
    "And they will be in everlasting torment.": "Their punishment in the Hereafter will never end. Eternal punishment awaits those who earned Allah's wrath through disbelief and wrongdoing. This permanent consequence should make everyone pause and examine their own alliances and loyalties."
  },
  81: {
    "Had they believed in Allah, the Prophet, and what has been revealed to him,": "If they truly believed in Allah—the same God they claim to worship—and if they believed in the Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) who was prophesied in their own scriptures, and if they believed in the Quran which confirms their original revelations—",
    "they would have never taken those ˹pagans˺ as allies.": "They would never have allied themselves with idol-worshippers against monotheists. True faith would have aligned them with the Muslims, not against them. Their choice of alliance exposed the weakness or absence of their claimed faith. Actions reveal true beliefs. You can claim to believe in God, but if you side with His enemies against His servants, your claim is hollow.",
    "But most of them are rebellious.": "The reality is that the majority of them are fasiqoon—rebellious transgressors who have departed from obedience to Allah. They have the name of faith but lack its reality. They carry the scriptures but don't follow them. Their rebellion is shown in their alliances, their actions, and their rejection of the final Prophet who came to confirm what they already had."
  },
  82: {
    "You will surely find the most bitter towards the believers to be the Jews and polytheists": "This is a factual observation about historical patterns of hostility. The Jews of Madinah and the Arab polytheists showed the most intense animosity toward the Muslims. Their opposition was deep-rooted—the Jews because they envied the final prophethood going to the Arabs rather than them, and the polytheists because Islam directly challenged their entire way of life and idol worship.",
    "and the most gracious to be those who call themselves Christian.": "In comparison, Christians generally showed less hostility and more openness to Islam. This was a relative comparison—not saying all Christians are allies, but that among the groups mentioned, they were often more receptive. The Negus (King of Abyssinia) who protected early Muslims is a famous example of this.",
    "That is because there are priests and monks among them": "One reason for their relative openness is that they had religious scholars and devout worshippers among them who recognized religious truth when they saw it. These individuals were trained in scripture and could see the parallels between Islamic teachings and what they already believed.",
    "and because they are not arrogant.": "Another key factor is humility. Unlike some who rejected Islam out of pride and jealousy, many Christians were humble enough to accept truth when it came to them. Arrogance is one of the biggest barriers to accepting guidance—it prevents people from admitting they might need to change."
  },
  83: {
    "When they listen to what has been revealed to the Messenger,": "When these sincere Christians hear the Quran being recited—its message of pure monotheism, its call to righteousness, its confirmation of previous prophets—something happens in their hearts.",
    "you see their eyes overflowing with tears for recognizing the truth.": "They weep not from sadness but from the overwhelming experience of recognizing truth. Their tears flow because they see in the Quran the same message Jesus brought—the worship of One God—but in its pure, undistorted form. When the delegation of Christians from Najran heard the Quran, many of them wept.",
    "They say, \"Our Lord! We believe, so count us among the witnesses.": "Their response is immediate faith. They don't argue or resist—they submit. They ask Allah to record them among the witnesses to truth, those who testified to the prophethood of Muhammad (peace be upon him) along with the earlier prophets."
  },
  84: {
    "Why should we not believe in Allah and the truth that has come to us?": "They express their logic beautifully: what reason could we possibly have to reject Allah and reject obvious truth? Their question implies that disbelief would be irrational.",
    "And we long for our Lord to include us in the company of the righteous.\"": "Their aspiration is to be counted among the righteous people of all ages—the prophets, the truthful, the martyrs, and the pious. They seek the best company for eternity."
  },
  85: {
    "So Allah will reward them for what they said": "Allah rewards sincere declarations of faith. Their words were not empty—they came from genuine hearts, and Allah accepted them.",
    "with Gardens under which rivers flow, to stay there forever.": "Their reward is Paradise—eternal gardens with flowing rivers, beauty beyond imagination, and permanent residence. No fear of losing it, no expiration date.",
    "And that is the reward of the good-doers.": "Those who do good (muhsineen)—who worship Allah with excellence and sincerity—earn this magnificent reward. These Christians became good-doers by accepting truth when it came to them."
  },
  86: {
    "As for those who disbelieve and reject Our signs,": "In contrast to those who accepted, there are those who deliberately disbelieve and deny Allah's clear proofs.",
    "they will be the residents of the Hellfire.": "Their permanent abode will be Hell. The contrast is stark: believers get eternal Paradise, rejecters get eternal Hell. The choice each person makes has eternal consequences."
  },
  87: {
    "O believers! Do not forbid the good things which Allah has made lawful for you,": "This verse addresses a tendency among some overly zealous believers to prohibit themselves from lawful pleasures—good food, marriage, comfortable living—thinking this makes them more pious. Some companions considered giving up meat, marriage, or sleep to devote themselves entirely to worship. But Islam is not monasticism. Allah made good things halal for you to enjoy, and declaring them forbidden is actually going against His wisdom.",
    "and do not transgress.": "At the same time, don't go to the other extreme of excess and indulgence. Balance is key—neither extreme deprivation nor excessive indulgence.",
    "Indeed, Allah does not like transgressors.": "Those who cross the limits—whether by forbidding what Allah allowed or by excessive indulgence—are not beloved to Allah. Islam is the middle path."
  },
  88: {
    "Eat of the good, lawful things provided to you by Allah.": "A positive command: enjoy what Allah has provided. Good, halal food is a blessing to be appreciated, not rejected. Eating well—within halal limits—is part of a balanced Islamic life.",
    "And be mindful of Allah in Whom you believe.": "While enjoying Allah's provisions, maintain consciousness of Him. Thank Him for what you have, don't waste, don't become obsessed with food, and remember that your faith should guide how you enjoy His blessings."
  },
  89: {
    "Allah will not call you to account for your thoughtless oaths,": "Unintentional oaths—things you say casually without meaning to make a serious vow, like saying \"wallahi\" (by Allah) out of habit in conversation—these are forgiven. Allah knows you didn't intend a binding oath.",
    "but He will hold you accountable for deliberate oaths.": "However, oaths you make seriously and intentionally are binding. If you swear by Allah to do something or not do something, that oath must be fulfilled or expiated.",
    "The penalty for a broken oath is to feed ten poor people from what you normally feed your own family,": "If you break a deliberate oath, the first option for expiation is to feed ten needy people. The food should be of average quality—what you would normally feed your own household, not the cheapest possible.",
    "or to clothe them,": "The second option is to provide clothing for ten needy people—enough to cover them adequately.",
    "or to free a bondsperson.": "The third option (in the context of that time) was to free a slave. This shows how Islam used every opportunity to encourage freeing those in bondage.",
    "But if none of this is affordable, then you must fast three days.": "For those who genuinely cannot afford to feed, clothe, or free someone, the alternative is fasting for three consecutive days. This ensures everyone has a way to expiate their broken oaths.",
    "This is the penalty for breaking your oaths.": "These are the specific, merciful ways Allah has provided to make amends for broken oaths.",
    "So be mindful of your oaths.": "Don't swear casually or frequently. When you do make an oath, take it seriously. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said that whoever swears by Allah should speak truth, and whoever is asked to swear by Allah should accept it.",
    "This is how Allah makes things clear to you, so perhaps you will be grateful.": "Allah explains these rulings clearly so you can follow them properly. This clarity is itself a blessing deserving gratitude."
  },
  90: {
    "O believers! Intoxicants,": "Khamr refers to anything that intoxicates—wine, beer, liquor, drugs, or any substance that clouds the mind and removes inhibitions. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said, \"Every intoxicant is khamr, and every khamr is forbidden.\"",
    "gambling,": "Maysir includes all forms of gambling—betting, lotteries, casino games, and any transaction where money is risked on uncertain outcomes for potential gain at others' expense.",
    "idols,": "Ansab refers to stone altars or idols set up for worship or sacrifice. Any object worshipped besides Allah falls into this category.",
    "and drawing lots for decisions": "Azlam were arrows used for divination—making decisions by chance rather than through reason, consultation, or prayer. This includes fortune-telling, horoscopes, and similar superstitious practices.",
    "are all evil of Satan's handiwork.": "All these things are described as rijs—filth, abomination—and attributed to Satan. They are his tools for leading people astray. This strong language indicates the severity of these prohibitions.",
    "So shun them so you may be successful.": "The command is to completely avoid them—not just limit them, but stay away entirely. Success in this life and the next depends on avoiding Satan's traps."
  },
  91: {
    "Satan's plan is to stir up hostility and hatred between you with intoxicants and gambling": "Allah reveals Satan's strategy. Alcohol removes inhibitions, leading to fights, violence, and broken relationships. How many families have been destroyed by alcohol? How many friendships ended over gambling debts? These are Satan's intended outcomes.",
    "and to prevent you from remembering Allah and praying.": "The deeper harm is spiritual. When intoxicated or obsessed with gambling, you cannot pray properly or remember Allah. You miss prayers, your mind is clouded, and your connection with Allah weakens. Satan's ultimate goal is to cut you off from your Creator.",
    "Will you not then abstain?": "After explaining the harms, Allah asks directly: knowing all this, will you still not stop? This rhetorical question challenges the believer to make the obvious choice. When this verse was revealed, the companions immediately poured out all their alcohol, and the streets of Madinah flowed with wine being discarded."
  },
  92: {
    "Obey Allah and obey the Messenger": "The command to obey is clear and repeated. Following Allah and His Messenger is the foundation of Islam.",
    "and beware!": "Be cautious and take these prohibitions seriously. Don't take them lightly or look for loopholes.",
    "But if you turn away, then know that Our Messenger's duty is only to deliver ˹the message˺ clearly.": "If you choose to disobey, the Prophet has fulfilled his responsibility by clearly conveying the message. He cannot force anyone to obey. The consequences of disobedience will fall on those who disobey."
  },
  93: {
    "There is no blame on those who believe and do good for what they had consumed before ˹the prohibition˺,": "When alcohol was prohibited, some companions worried about those who had died before the prohibition while consuming wine—were they sinful? This verse clarifies: no blame attaches to what was consumed before the prohibition came. People are not accountable for rules that hadn't been revealed yet.",
    "as long as they fear Allah, have faith, and do what is good;": "The condition is that they maintained taqwa, true faith, and righteous deeds according to what was required at that time.",
    "then they believe and act virtuously,": "And they continued in faith and good works as new guidance came.",
    "then become fully mindful ˹of Allah˺ and do righteous deeds.": "And they progressed to higher levels of God-consciousness and excellence in action. The repetition emphasizes ongoing growth in faith.",
    "For Allah loves the good-doers.": "Those who strive for excellence (ihsan) in their worship and conduct are beloved to Allah. Past actions done in ignorance are forgiven when followed by sincere faith and good deeds."
  },
  94: {
    "O believers! Allah will surely test you with game within the reach of your hands and spears": "During pilgrimage, Allah will test you by placing game animals within easy reach. They'll be close enough to catch by hand or spear. This is a deliberate test.",
    "to distinguish those who fear Him in secret.": "The purpose is to reveal who truly fears Allah even when no one is watching. During ihram, hunting is forbidden, and this tests your obedience when you could easily get away with violation. True taqwa shows when you obey Allah without external enforcement.",
    "Whoever transgresses from now on will suffer a painful punishment.": "After this clear warning, anyone who hunts during ihram will face severe punishment. The excuse of ignorance is removed."
  },
  95: {
    "O believers! Do not kill game while on pilgrimage.": "A direct prohibition: when in the state of ihram, do not hunt or kill land animals.",
    "Whoever kills game intentionally must compensate by offering its equivalence—as judged by two just men among you—to be offered at the Sacred House,": "If someone deliberately kills game during ihram, they must offer a domestic animal equivalent in value to what they killed. Two trustworthy Muslims determine what's equivalent. This animal is then sacrificed near the Kaaba.",
    "or by feeding the needy,": "Alternatively, the value of the animal can be used to feed poor people.",
    "or by fasting so that they may taste the consequences of their violations.": "Or they can fast a number of days equivalent to the value. The fasting makes them physically experience the weight of their violation.",
    "Allah has forgiven what has been done.": "Past violations before this ruling are forgiven. Don't worry about what happened before you knew.",
    "But those who persist will be punished by Allah.": "However, anyone who repeats the violation after knowing the rule will face Allah's punishment.",
    "And Allah is Almighty, capable of punishment.": "Allah has full power to punish transgressors. This isn't an empty threat."
  },
  96: {
    "It is lawful for you to hunt and eat seafood,": "An important exception: sea creatures—fish and other seafood—are permissible to catch and eat even during ihram.",
    "as a provision for you and for travellers.": "This is a mercy, especially for travelers and pilgrims who may depend on fishing for food during their journey.",
    "But hunting on land is forbidden to you while on pilgrimage.": "The prohibition specifically applies to land animals. This distinction makes the rule practical and clear.",
    "Be mindful of Allah to Whom you all will be gathered.": "Remember that you will return to Allah and be held accountable for all your actions, including whether you respected these sacred limits."
  },
  97: {
    "Allah has made the Ka'bah—the Sacred House—a sanctuary of well-being for all people,": "The Kaaba serves as a source of stability, spiritual well-being, and unity for humanity. It is the qiblah (direction of prayer) for all Muslims and the destination of pilgrimage. Around it, people find peace, forgiveness, and renewal.",
    "along with the sacred months,": "The four sacred months provide regular periods of peace and security, allowing people to travel for pilgrimage and trade safely.",
    "the sacrificial animals, and the ˹offerings decorated with˺ garlands.": "The animals brought for sacrifice and the garlands that mark them are all part of the sacred system that ensures smooth pilgrimage and maintains the sanctity of the journey.",
    "All this so you may know that Allah knows whatever is in the heavens and whatever is on the earth,": "These intricate arrangements demonstrate Allah's comprehensive knowledge. He knows what benefits humanity spiritually, socially, and practically.",
    "and that He has ˹perfect˺ knowledge of everything.": "Nothing escapes Allah's knowledge—not the movements of pilgrims, not the thoughts in hearts, not any detail of creation."
  },
  98: {
    "Know that Allah is severe in punishment": "For those who violate His sacred limits and persist in sin, Allah's punishment is severe. This creates healthy fear that prevents transgression.",
    "and that He is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful.": "Yet for those who repent and return to Him, He is Most Forgiving and Merciful. This balance of fear and hope is essential in Islam. Neither despair of His mercy nor feel safe from His punishment."
  },
  99: {
    "The Messenger's duty is only to deliver ˹the message˺.": "The Prophet's responsibility is to convey guidance clearly. He cannot force anyone to believe or obey. Once he delivers the message, people are responsible for their own choices.",
    "And Allah ˹fully˺ knows what you reveal and what you conceal.": "Your public actions and your private intentions—Allah knows them all. You can hide nothing from Him, so be sincere in your obedience."
  },
  100: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Good and evil are not equal,": "This is a fundamental principle. Good and evil, halal and haram, truth and falsehood—they are never the same, regardless of how they appear.",
    "though you may be dazzled by the abundance of evil.": "Sometimes evil appears in large quantities—many people do it, it seems profitable, it's everywhere in society. But quantity doesn't make it good. A small amount of good is better than mountains of evil. Quality over quantity.",
    "So be mindful of Allah, O people of reason, so you may be successful.\"": "Those with intelligence should use their reason to distinguish good from evil, and then have the taqwa to choose good even when evil seems more abundant or attractive. This is the path to true success."
  },
  101: {
    "O believers! Do not ask about any matter which, if made clear to you, may disturb you.": "Don't pry into matters that Allah has left general or undefined. Some companions would ask excessive questions like \"Who is my real father?\" or \"Will I go to Paradise?\" or hypotheticals that could lead to stricter rulings. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said the worst sinners among Muslims are those who ask about something not prohibited, causing it to become prohibited because of their question.",
    "But if you inquire about what is being revealed in the Quran, it will be made clear to you.": "Legitimate questions about understanding current revelations are welcome. Seeking clarity on what's being taught is different from prying into unnecessary matters.",
    "Allah has forgiven what was done ˹in the past˺.": "What has passed before these clarifications is forgiven. Don't stress about matters Allah has already overlooked.",
    "And Allah is All-Forgiving, Most Forbearing.": "Allah's forgiveness and patience with human curiosity and mistakes is vast."
  },
  102: {
    "Some people before you asked such questions then denied their answers.": "Previous nations asked their prophets unnecessary questions. When they received answers that didn't please them, they rejected the guidance entirely. Their excessive questioning led them to disbelief. The Children of Israel, when told to sacrifice a cow, kept asking for specifications until the simple command became difficult. Learn from their mistakes."
  },
  103: {
    "Allah has never ordained the ˹so-called˺ baḥîrah, sâ'ibah, waṣîlah, and ḥâm camels.": "These were categories of animals that pre-Islamic Arabs dedicated to idols and made forbidden for various reasons based on superstition. Bahirah was a she-camel whose ear was split; sa'ibah was set free for idols; wasilah was a she-camel that gave birth to females; ham was a male camel that sired ten offspring. All these distinctions had no basis in divine law.",
    "But the disbelievers just fabricate lies about Allah,": "They invented these rules and falsely attributed them to Allah or ancient tradition. This is religious fraud—making up rules and claiming divine authority for them.",
    "and most of them lack understanding.": "They don't use their intellect to question these baseless traditions. Blind following of ancestors without critical thinking leads to such errors."
  },
  104: {
    "When it is said to them, \"Come to Allah's revelations and to the Messenger,\"": "When invited to follow divine guidance and the Prophet's teachings instead of their superstitions—",
    "they reply, \"What we found our forefathers practicing is good enough for us.\"": "They refuse, citing ancestral tradition as their authority. \"Our fathers did it this way\" becomes their excuse for rejecting truth.",
    "˹Would they still do so,˺ even if their forefathers had absolutely no knowledge or guidance?": "Allah challenges this logic: what if your ancestors were ignorant and misguided? Would you still follow them off a cliff? Blind adherence to tradition without evaluation is foolish. Truth should be followed regardless of whether your ancestors knew it."
  },
  105: {
    "O believers! You are accountable only for yourselves.": "Focus on your own spiritual state and actions. You cannot control what others do, but you can control yourself.",
    "It will not harm you if someone chooses to deviate—as long as you are ˹rightly˺ guided.": "Others going astray won't hurt you on the Day of Judgment if you yourself are on the right path. However, this doesn't mean abandoning the duty to enjoin good and forbid evil. Abu Bakr explained this verse: you should still advise others, but if they refuse, their misguidance won't harm you as long as you did your part and maintained your own guidance.",
    "To Allah you will all return,": "Everyone returns to Allah—both the guided and the misguided.",
    "and He will inform you of what you used to do.": "Allah will make clear who was right and who was wrong, and reward or punish accordingly."
  },
  106: {
    "O believers! When death approaches any of you, call upon two just Muslim men to witness as you make a bequest;": "When making a will near death, have two trustworthy Muslim men witness it. This protects the rights of heirs and ensures the deceased's wishes are properly recorded.",
    "otherwise, two non-Muslims if you are afflicted with death while on a journey.": "If you're traveling and no Muslims are available, non-Muslim witnesses are acceptable. This shows Islam's practical approach—the priority is having witnesses to protect rights.",
    "If you doubt ˹their testimony˺, keep them after prayer and let them testify under oath ˹saying˺,": "If there's suspicion about the witnesses' honesty, detain them after prayer (a solemn time) and have them swear—",
    "\"By Allah! We would never sell our testimony for any price, even in favour of a close relative,": "They must swear they haven't been bribed or influenced by family ties to lie.",
    "nor withhold the testimony of Allah. Otherwise, we would surely be sinful.\"": "They affirm they're telling the complete truth, acknowledging that hiding testimony would make them sinners."
  },
  107: {
    "If they are found guilty ˹of false testimony˺,": "If evidence emerges that the original witnesses lied—",
    "let the deceased's two closest heirs affected by the bequest replace the witnesses": "Two of the rightful heirs who were wronged by the false testimony come forward.",
    "and testify under oath ˹saying˺, \"By Allah! Our testimony is truer than theirs.": "They swear that their account is more accurate than the lying witnesses.",
    "We have not transgressed. Otherwise, we would surely be wrongdoers.\"": "They affirm they're not exceeding their rights or making false claims themselves."
  },
  108: {
    "In this way it is more likely that witnesses will give true testimony": "This procedure—with oaths and the possibility of counter-oaths—encourages honesty from the start.",
    "or else fear that their oaths could be refuted by those of the heirs.": "Witnesses know that if they lie, the heirs can challenge them with their own oaths. This fear keeps them honest.",
    "Be mindful of Allah and obey.": "Throughout all legal matters, maintain consciousness of Allah and follow His guidance.",
    "For Allah does not guide the rebellious people.": "Those who persist in rebellion and dishonesty lose access to divine guidance."
  },
  109: {
    "˹Consider˺ the Day Allah will gather the messengers and say, \"What response did you receive?\"": "On the Day of Judgment, Allah will assemble all the prophets and ask them how their nations responded to their messages. This is a scene of tremendous gravity—even prophets will be questioned.",
    "They will reply, \"We have no knowledge ˹compared to You˺!": "The messengers humbly defer to Allah. Despite their knowledge, they acknowledge their limitations compared to Allah's absolute knowledge. They don't claim to know the hidden intentions of people's hearts or what happened after their deaths.",
    "You ˹alone˺ are indeed the Knower of all unseen.\"": "Only Allah knows the full truth of what was in people's hearts and what they truly deserve. This is ultimate humility from the most honored of creation."
  },
  110: {
    "And ˹on Judgment Day˺ Allah will say, \"O Jesus, son of Mary! Remember My favour upon you and your mother:": "Allah will remind Jesus of His blessings, establishing clearly that Jesus's abilities came from Allah, not from any divine nature of his own.",
    "how I supported you with the holy spirit": "Jibreel (Gabriel) assisted and strengthened Jesus throughout his mission. This holy spirit is an angel, not part of a trinity.",
    "so you spoke to people in ˹your˺ infancy and adulthood.": "Jesus miraculously spoke as a baby in the cradle to defend his mother Mary from accusations. He also taught as an adult. Both were by Allah's power.",
    "How I taught you writing, wisdom, the Torah, and the Gospel.": "Allah bestowed knowledge upon Jesus—literacy, wisdom, and understanding of both the Torah and the Gospel revealed to him.",
    "How you moulded a bird from clay—by My Will—and breathed into it and it became a ˹real˺ bird—by My Will.": "Jesus could shape clay into bird forms and bring them to life—but note the repeated phrase \"by My Will.\" The power was Allah's; Jesus was the instrument. This miracle demonstrated prophethood, not divinity.",
    "How you healed the blind and the lepers—by My Will.": "Jesus cured those born blind and those suffering from leprosy—incurable conditions at the time. Again, \"by My Will\" emphasizes the source of the power.",
    "How you brought the dead to life—by My Will.": "Jesus could restore the dead to life—another tremendous miracle, but still \"by My Will.\" Only Allah truly gives life and death.",
    "How I prevented the Children of Israel from harming you when you came to them with clear proofs": "When enemies wanted to kill Jesus, Allah protected him. They couldn't harm him until Allah's plan for him was complete.",
    "and the disbelievers among them said, \"This is nothing but pure magic.\"": "Despite these obvious miracles, the disbelievers dismissed them as magic. When hearts are sealed, even the clearest signs are rejected."
  },
  111: {
    "And how I inspired the disciples, \"Believe in Me and My messenger!\"": "Allah inspired the hearts of Jesus's disciples (hawariyyeen) to believe in Allah and in Jesus as His messenger—not as God, but as a messenger.",
    "They declared, \"We believe and bear witness that we fully submit ˹to Allah˺.\"": "The disciples declared their Islam—their submission to Allah. They were Muslims in the true sense, following the prophet of their time with complete submission to the One God."
  },
  112: {
    "˹Remember˺ when the disciples asked, \"O Jesus, son of Mary! Would your Lord be willing to send down to us a table spread with food from heaven?\"": "The disciples made an unusual request—they wanted a miraculous feast sent down from heaven. The phrasing \"would your Lord be willing\" shows they wondered if Allah would grant such a request.",
    "Jesus answered, \"Fear Allah if you are ˹truly˺ believers.\"": "Jesus initially cautioned them. True believers should be content with the signs already given. Demanding extra miracles can be a sign of weak faith. He encouraged them to strengthen their taqwa rather than seek more signs."
  },
  113: {
    "They said, \"We ˹only˺ wish to eat from it to reassure our hearts,": "They explained their reasoning: they wanted to strengthen their faith. Seeing such a miracle would settle any remaining doubts.",
    "to verify you are indeed truthful to us,": "They wanted additional confirmation that Jesus was truly Allah's messenger.",
    "and to become its witnesses.\"": "They wanted to be eyewitnesses to this miracle so they could testify to future generations about what they saw."
  },
  114: {
    "Jesus, son of Mary, prayed, \"O Allah, our Lord!": "Jesus turns to Allah in supplication, showing his servitude. He doesn't produce the miracle himself—he asks Allah for it.",
    "Send us from heaven a table spread with food as a feast for us—the first and last of us—": "He asks for a celebratory feast that would be a blessed occasion for all believers, present and future.",
    "and as a sign from You.": "Let it serve as proof of Your power and confirmation of my prophethood.",
    "Provide for us! You are indeed the Best Provider.\"": "Jesus acknowledges Allah as the ultimate Provider. He asks for provision while affirming Allah's attribute as the best of providers."
  },
  115: {
    "Allah answered, \"I am sending it down to you.": "Allah grants the request. The miracle will be sent.",
    "But whoever among you denies afterwards": "With increased proof comes increased responsibility. After witnessing such a clear sign—",
    "will be subjected to a torment I have never inflicted on anyone of My creation.\"": "Those who disbelieve after seeing this miracle will face unprecedented punishment. The greater the evidence, the less excuse for disbelief. This warning is severe because rejecting truth after such clear proof is the height of ingratitude and stubbornness."
  },
  116: {
    "And ˹on Judgment Day˺ Allah will say, \"O Jesus, son of Mary! Did you ever ask the people to worship you and your mother as gods besides Allah?\"": "Allah will question Jesus directly on the Day of Judgment about the worship Christians directed to him and Mary. This question establishes Jesus's innocence of the beliefs later attributed to him.",
    "He will answer, \"Glory be to You!": "Jesus begins with glorification—tanzih—declaring Allah free of any partners or equals.",
    "How could I ever say what I had no right to say?": "Jesus expresses impossibility—he could never claim divinity because he had no right to such a claim. Only Allah deserves worship.",
    "If I had said such a thing, you would have certainly known it.": "Allah's knowledge is complete. If Jesus had ever uttered such blasphemy, Allah would know. But He knows Jesus never did.",
    "You know what is ˹hidden˺ within me, but I do not know what is within You.": "Jesus acknowledges the difference between Creator and creation. Allah knows Jesus's innermost thoughts, but Jesus cannot comprehend Allah's essence.",
    "Indeed, You ˹alone˺ are the Knower of all unseen.\"": "All knowledge of the unseen belongs to Allah. Jesus confirms his status as a limited creation before the unlimited Creator."
  },
  117: {
    "I never told them anything except what You ordered me to say: \"Worship Allah—my Lord and your Lord!\"": "Jesus's message was clear and consistent: worship Allah alone. He called Allah \"my Lord\"—proving Jesus himself worshipped Allah. His message was the same as every prophet: pure monotheism.",
    "And I was witness over them as long as I remained among them.": "While alive among them, Jesus watched over his followers and guided them correctly.",
    "But when You took me,": "After Allah raised Jesus up (Muslims believe Jesus was not crucified but raised to heaven), he was no longer directly witnessing his followers' actions.",
    "You were the Witness over them—and You are a Witness over all things.": "Once Jesus was gone, only Allah observed what his followers did—how they eventually distorted his teachings. Allah witnessed everything."
  },
  118: {
    "If You punish them, they belong to You after all.": "Jesus leaves judgment to Allah. If Allah chooses to punish those who went astray, He has every right—they are His creation, His servants.",
    "But if You forgive them, You are surely the Almighty, All-Wise.\"": "And if Allah chooses to forgive, that too is within His power and wisdom. Jesus doesn't presume to dictate to Allah. He submits the matter entirely to divine justice and mercy. Note: he doesn't say \"You are Forgiving, Merciful\" (which might imply he's asking for their forgiveness), but \"Almighty, All-Wise\"—leaving the decision completely to Allah's power and wisdom."
  },
  119: {
    "Allah will declare, \"This is the Day when ˹only˺ the faithful will benefit from their faithfulness.": "On the Day of Judgment, truth and sincerity will finally matter. All the truthfulness in belief, word, and deed will pay off. The hypocrites and liars will gain nothing from their deceptions.",
    "Theirs are Gardens under which rivers flow, to stay there for ever and ever.": "The truthful believers receive eternal Paradise—gardens of unimaginable beauty with rivers flowing beneath, and permanent residence with no end.",
    "Allah is pleased with them and they are pleased with Him.": "This is the greatest reward—mutual pleasure between Creator and creation. Allah is satisfied with them, and they are completely content with what Allah has given them. No resentment, no regret, no unfulfilled desires.",
    "That is the ultimate triumph.\"": "Al-fawz al-'azim—the greatest success. This is what every human should strive for. All worldly successes pale in comparison."
  },
  120: {
    "To Allah ˹alone˺ belongs the kingdom of the heavens and the earth and everything within.": "The surah concludes by affirming Allah's absolute sovereignty. Everything in existence belongs to Him—the heavens, the earth, and all creatures within them. Jesus doesn't share this dominion; neither does any other being.",
    "And He is Most Capable of everything.": "There is nothing Allah cannot do. He can create, destroy, reward, punish, forgive, or judge—all with perfect capability. This final statement reinforces every theme of the surah: Allah's power, His right to legislate, His authority to judge, and the ultimate return of all matters to Him. With this, Surah Al-Ma'idah ends, having covered laws of food, contracts, purification, justice, relations with People of the Book, and the true nature of Jesus—all pointing back to the absolute oneness and sovereignty of Allah."
  }
};